<HEAD>Seven Killed in Two Small Plane Crashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with three more bodies found in South Carolina.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A twin-engine airplane en route from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> crashed in rainy weather Tuesday, killing four people, and three others died when a small plane crashed in the rugged White Cloud Mountains in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. The Beechcraft Duke en route to the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> crashed about 5 p.m. near Interstate 26 on the 2,300-acre site of the <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> plant in central <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Lexington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` Everything was routine,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` All of a sudden, they lost radar contact.'' One body was found within an hour of the crash and rescue workers found the other three bodies in the plane about 9 p.m., Ms. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. The rescue workers waited for <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> investigators to arrive on the scene before entering the wreckage. `` We had pieces of the plane scattered a quarter-mile away,'' she said. The victims had not been identified late Tuesday, Ms. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, the twin-engine, six-seat <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aztec </ORGANIZATION> was en route to <LOCATION> Challis </LOCATION> when it crashed in mid-afternoon. The flight had originated in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and stopped in <LOCATION> Wenatchee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, chief of the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> Division of Aeronautics in <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>. The cause of the crash was not immediately known, but snow, hail, wind and rainstorms were reported in parts of central <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> at the time. The names of the victims were being withheld until relatives could be notified.
