<FIRST>r i PM-PolishPolitician     06-20 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polish Politician,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Stopped Solidarity Juggernaut Admired for Making Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PILA, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It took a free-spending entrepreneur to deprive Solidarity of a clean sweep of the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first freely elected legislative chamber. A Communist-backed businessman. <PERSON> Henryk </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON>, who has made millions processing dead animals, edged out <PERSON> Piotr </PERSON> <PERSON> Baumgart </PERSON>, an activist of the independent farmers' union Rural Solidarity, in Sunday's runoff, unofficial returns showed Monday <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON> had drawn the Communist coalition's biggest pre-election crowd _ 50,000 people at <LOCATION> Pila </LOCATION> stadium for free sausages and beer and a drawing with prizes including a tractor, a color television and a videocassette recorder. Tickets for the drawing had been handed out free in the province's myriad small agricultural villages beforehand. <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON> will be a minority of one in the new 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> that is to convene next month along with the more powerful lower house, or Sejm, which the ruling Communists dominate because opposition candidates were only allowed to run for one-third of its seats. A visit to <LOCATION> Pila </LOCATION> on Sunday gave some hint of <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON>'s assets. On the streets of the 70,000-resident western provincial town _ unusually prosperous - and tidy-looking by Polish standards _ soldiers from nearby military bases strolled arm-in-arm with girlfriends eating ice cream cones <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON>'s moustachioed face stared out at passers-by from election posters plastered nearly everywhere, in store windows, walls and road overpasses. There were also posters attacking <PERSON> Baumgart </PERSON> as an interloper because he comes from <LOCATION> Szczecin </LOCATION>, about 90 miles away. A journalist for Solidarity's <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> estimated <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON> put 200 million zlotys -LRB- $ 235,000 -RRB- into the campaign. It was believed to be the most expensive political campaign ever launched for an individual in postwar <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. In the nearby town of <LOCATION> Smilowo </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON>'s Farmutil company is headquartered, the polling station was doing a brisk business Sunday in an apparent show of local pride in the town's favorite son. But <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON> himself was absent. Attending to business first, he was at an international trade fair in <LOCATION> Poznan </LOCATION>. His Farmutil company, located on 345 acres at the end of a specially built road in <LOCATION> Smilowo </LOCATION>, gives a shiny neat appearance. But it belches an obnoxious odor over the rolling landscape, as dead farm animals and meat plant scraps are boiled down into fats and fodders for delivery by <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON>'s truck fleet to customers around <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. An employee, speaking as flies buzzed around, said the stench would disappear as soon as a new hermetically sealed processing system is completed. The 210-worker plant has sprung up in the past seven years. <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON> left his job as <PERSON> Pila </PERSON> tourism director and was kicked out of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> during Solidarity's 1980-81 heyday for alleged mismanagement. The plant now produces mainly fodder for animals, but plans are for it to expand into poultry raising, fertilizer production and slaughtering. The company makes an estimated 3 billion zlotys -LRB- $ 3.5 million -RRB- annually and published reports say <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON> as a result can tool around town in either one of two new Mercedes. `` He's got everything he could want in life, and now he wants other people to have more too,'' said <PERSON> Henryk </PERSON> <PERSON> Mocho </PERSON>, a Stoklosa campaign worker. `` He has very good organizing ability. He is the man who started this whole enterprise from nothing, and now people can make a good living here.'' <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Malecki </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Pila </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> passed Sunday afternoon quietly at the opposition's empty campaign office with <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Woznicki </PERSON>, his former jailmate from 1982, the year thousands of Solidarity activists spent time in jail after authorities crushed their movement. They anticipated <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON>'s win, but treated it philosophically. `` We are aware that <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> does not begin and end at <LOCATION> Pila </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Malecki </PERSON> said. No matter what the outcome, the local committee would share in Solidarity's `` great success'' because it elected one other <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> candidate and two members to the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> from the city, he said. <PERSON> Wozniaki </PERSON>, a Solidarity activist at the town's largest industry, a light-bulb factory, said his forces were outgunned by <PERSON> Stoklosa </PERSON>'s massive poster campaign and Western-style gimmicks He blamed a lack of money, paper and printing machines and suggested Polish-Americans send more material aid to Solidarity next time. `` Tell them that a free <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> depends on them too,'' he said, only half-jokingly.
