<HEAD>Pianist Resumes Performances After 11-Year Hiatus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with end of performance, 13 curtain
calls. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Cliburn played...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON BEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After an 11-year hiatus, pianist <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> resumed his public performances Monday night to thunderous applause with a concert dedicated to two late friends. The audience called the pianist back to the stage 13 times after he completed his program of <PERSON> Liszt </PERSON>'s Piano Concerto No. 1 and <PERSON> Tchaikovsky </PERSON>'s Piano Concerto No. 1. <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> ended the evening with four encores. `` This is a very sentimental evening for me,'' <PERSON> Clibuurn </PERSON> told the audience before the performance. `` This is an evening of remembrance of two wonderful friends.'' The pianist dedicated the concert at the open-air <ORGANIZATION> Mann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> to <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Ormandy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fredric </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ormandy </PERSON>, who died in 1985, was music director of the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orchestra </LOCATION> for 44 years. <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador, headed the summer concert festival at the music center from 1949 until his death in 1987. <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> played with <PERSON> Ormandy </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> musicians within weeks of gaining world fame for winning the first <ORGANIZATION> Tchaikovsky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Competition </ORGANIZATION> in 1958. The relationship yielded numerous concerts and recordings. He also played in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> in 1978, the year he quit performed publicly, weary from a schedule that included 100 concerts a year. He said he chose the Liszt to honor <PERSON> Ormandy </PERSON>'s Hungarian background. The program concluded with <PERSON> Tchaikovsky </PERSON>'s Piano Concerto No. 1. <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> spent the morning practicing with the orchestra and the afternoon shopping in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` It's so good to be back with the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orchestra </LOCATION>. It seems like I never left,'' <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> said after the practice session. Among his favorite venues, <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> always listed <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>'s theater in <LOCATION> Fairmont </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, where he would often play to the audience long after the orchestra musicians had left for the night. Proceeds from Monday night's concert will help finance the orchestra's free summer series, which <PERSON> Ormandy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> began. <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> of Princess <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, who traveled with <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> for six months two decades ago for a film project, said the years dropped away from the pianist in profile. `` You would never know it has been 11 years since he appeared before an audience like this,'' <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> said. Since 1978, he had performed in public only twice _ in December 1987 and in January 1988 for private gatherings honoring, respectively, Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and the Bob Hope Cultural Center.
