<HEAD>Mountain Goat Herd to be Returned to Mount Juneau</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After years of absence, mountain goats will be returned to the steep slopes of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION> with the help of tranquilizers, helicopters and thousands of dollars in donations. Volunteers plan to relocate at least 10 wild goats from a remote site south of <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION> or the Olympic Peninsula of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in late summer or early fall. The goal is to restore a herd of goats that can be viewed by residents and tourists in downtown <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION>, which sits in the narrow valley between <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roberts </LOCATION>. `` If all goes well, in a year or two or five we'll have a population that will create splinter groups to proliferate in valleys from <LOCATION> Taku </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Berners </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>,'' said project coordinator <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a member of the state Fish and Game Board. `` <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION> used to be goat habitat,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said Monday. `` Goats were there quite commonly back in the mining days, the early days of <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION>.'' However, overhunting led to the goats' disappearance near the <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> city. Although goat hunting has been banned in the area for several years, the goats have never returned. Since the <ORGANIZATION> Juneau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> began soliciting money for the project in February, it has collected about $ 9,500 in money and services _ enough to start the project, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> hopes to have $ 12,000 by the time the relocation begins, and said he has been encouraged by the public response. Donations have included helicopter time from a local charter outfit, a $ 1,000 check and $ 30 worth of quarters that a little girl collected in a bag. If the goats can not be captured south of <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Whiting </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, the volunteers will turn to the <LOCATION> Olympic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> where the goat population has become a nuisance. `` We actally gave the goats to the Olympic Peninsula in the first place. We would be getting the same stock back,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. State wildlife officials will tranquilize the goats, which will be transported to the mountain by helicopters. Officials hope to get at least three males and seven females to ensure that the population grows. Radio collars will be put on some of the goats so their movement can be monitored.
