<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the belief that these are vinegar's salad days, a bus driver has brought out a book entirely on the centuries-old food seasoning. `` Vinegar is something more than just to put in your salad,'' <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Diggs </PERSON> said at a news conference Monday flanked by various vinegars. One displayed was the gourmet's balsamic, which can cost up to $ 30 for a few ounces. <PERSON> Diggs </PERSON> believes his 259-page book `` Vinegar'' is the most complete ever written on the subject. Vinegar, from the French word for `` sour wine,'' is the end product of fermentation. Anything that can be fermented into alcohol _ including fruits, grains, orange juice, molasses, honey _ can be made into vinegar. The tome covers vinegar's history, commercial production, how to make it at home, and medicinal uses. `` To remove a freckle, apply vinegar,'' the author prescribes. Soda mixed with vinegar will deal with heartburn, while hay fever can be combated by inhaling horseradish and vinegar several times a day. <PERSON> Diggs </PERSON> even has a chapter on vinegar trivia. `` If one dreams about vinegar, it signifies jealousy or a quarrel,'' he advises, and `` Never give vinegar away or your luck will go with it.'' The author, a Zen Buddhist, said he planned to use profits from the $ 24.95 book to establish a monastic hermitage. He also expressed gratitude to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s Municipal Railway for helping make his book possible. `` I wrote a lot of the book on the bus,'' he confided.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Summer is coming to central <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Camas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prairie </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroud </PERSON> once again has his eye on Soldier Mountain's last patch of snow _ and on his friends <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> and Wes Fields. As they have for more than a decade, the three have placed bets on when the final remnant of winter will disappear. With dinner for the winner at stake, it's a bet that nature has not always been allowed to settle. <PERSON> Stroud </PERSON> is betting again that the snow will still being visible on Aug. 10, but he knows a lot can happen by then. Faced with losing several years ago when the snow was nearly gone days before his target date, <PERSON> Stroud </PERSON> sent his two sons up the mountain to stretch white sheets on the ground. Sheets can look a lot like snow from 10 miles away, but someone picked them up early and <PERSON> Stroud </PERSON> lost. Another year, <PERSON> Stroud </PERSON> was ready to collect a free meal because a tiny patch of snow was visible the afternoon before the day of reckoning. But the next day, the mountain looked bare. As it turned out, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> had driven into the high country with Fields to shovel dirt over the snow patch. Winning that bet cost them about $ 500, but as Fields said, `` Winning is the thing, you see.''
