<HEAD>Missile-Engine Contractor, On Time, On Budget, Out of Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> says a cruise-missile engine agreement with a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> company will be canceled even though the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> found the deal led to lower prices. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> will cancel the agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walled </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, on grounds that it should not have committed the service to future contracts, <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> wrote last week to Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich. `` For each of the past 10 years, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> has submitted competitive prices well below those of its competitor for production engines,'' <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> wrote `` We do believe that the fact of competition has benefited the taxpayer by creating an added incentive to lower prices.'' He said <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> has exceeded its reliability goals and delivered every engine ahead of the contract date. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> in 1978 signed an agreement that would allow a competitor, <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, to use <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' technology to build cruise-missile engines for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. In return, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> guaranteed it would buy 240 engines a year from <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION>, plus 25 percent of any additional purchases up to 1,200 engines annually. <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON>, in an April letter to <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, had written that the decade-old agreement with <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> was `` severely limiting our contracting options and decisions, in a manner which we believe inconsistent with sound procurement policy and the public interest.'' <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> also said in April that <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION>'s prices had become `` very competitive'' with <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> beginning last year. The April letter was made public by a whistle-blower group called the Project on Military Procurement. <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> released last week's letter <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s cancellation of the 1978 agreement `` in no way implies criticism of <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s integrity or performance.'' `` We appreciate the emphasis on ethics that has always been part of <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s management, and we consider it an outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> contractor,'' <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> wrote. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Lt. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said Monday he could not immediately comment on the two letters. <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said that even though the agreement was still being canceled, `` There are some real differences'' between <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON>'s April letter and what he wrote last week `` Maybe he recognizes that his first letter was really not the most accurate reflection of the situation.''
