<HEAD>Worst Wind Erosion in 30 Years Sweeps Over Great Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wind erosion over the winter inflicted its worst damage in three decades on the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, ripping away topsoil over 14.3 million acres, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. `` The big reason for the increase is the drought,'' soil conservation service chief Wilson Scaling said Monday. `` Not only was it dry but it meant we went into the wind erosion season with inadequate vegetative cover and little residue to protect the soil from blowing.'' He said the last time the May-November wind erosion season wrought so much damage on the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> was when 15 million acres were damaged in 1954-55, when the department first began to keep such records. In the worst day of the season, winds of up to 80 miles an hour swooped through on <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> on March 14, damaging 4.8 million acres. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> was the hardest hit state, with more than 5 million acres damaged. It was a record for the state. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> was second with 2.3 million acres harmed and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> followed with almost 2 million acres damaged. More than 90 percent of the damage is on lands being used for crops. The rest is on rangeland. Wind erosion damage last year uprooted soil from some 12 million acres. The department said farmers used emergency tillage on 3 million acres, a system under which topsoil with sufficient moiture is roughened to prevent blowing. More than half of the emergency tillage was in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Here is a list of the amount of acres damaged in each <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> state: <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> 1,832,000; <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> 191,600; <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> 2,297,700; <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> 678,600; <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> 552,700; <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> 1,403,700; <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> 5,126,300; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> 118,000; <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> 111,900; <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> 1,979,600.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wheat production in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> should fall slightly below previous estimates for the next year, suggesting supplies already reduced by last year's drought will remain tight, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> says. With world stocks already at their lowest in more than a decade, prices could be somewhat skittish in the crop year that began June 1, responding sharply to changes in growing conditions and import demand, the department said. A drop of $ 10 a ton in the price of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat in recent weeks represents an example of this sensitivity, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said in its monthly World Grain Situation and Outlook report. Despite such fluctuations, however, prices should remain strong on the whole, the department said. It said the overall strength in prices combined with an improvement in crop prospects in some of the traditional importing countries is expected to reduce world demand from the level of a year earlier. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said the major change will come in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where wheat imports are expected to decline by around 20 percent to 12 million tons. Estimated exports by the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> remain the same as previously, but the forecast of production has been lowered to reflect a smaller than expected crop of durum, the wheat used for pasta. The report said that might mean increased <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> imports of North American durum and might even trigger a cutback in Italian semolina exports to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The European Community estimate was for 77.8 million metric tons, down from 78.5 million last month. The estimate of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production was 55.2 million, down from 55.8 million in last month's report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parrot lovers and other buyers of exotic birds are getting a stern warning from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> to make certain their pets meet federal import requirements. The warning has been brought on by an outbreak of exotic <ORGANIZATION> Newcastle </ORGANIZATION> disease among 17 <ORGANIZATION> Amazon </ORGANIZATION> parrots, sun cockatoos and other birds owned by a <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> collector. Seven of the parrots were purchased from a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> dealer on May 19 and became ill. They and 12 other birds were dead by June 14. Meanwhile, the collector had sold some of the birds to five pet stores and a number of individual purchasers. The birds were tested by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterinary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ames </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, operated by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. They were found to have exotic Newcastle disease. To prevent further spread of the disease, the collector's 60 remaining birds were destroyed, the department said. It said it will pay the collector more than $ 45,000 in indemnities for the destruction of his collection. Exotic Newcastle disease is a virus that is deadly to all birds and could be a major problem for the commercial poultry industry, although no commercial flocks have been infected yet. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Slagle </PERSON>, acting director of the inspection service, said smuggled birds enter the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by the hundreds following the winter breeding season and often carry exotic Newcastle disease without showing symptoms. He said exotic birds imported into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must be declared to federal inspectors, carry appropriate permits and enter a mimimum 30-day quarantine. The Agriculture Department tests them for disease during that time.
