<FIRST>r w PM-HeartDisease     06-20 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heart Disease,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heart Disease Death Rates Declining In West, Up in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Heart disease death rates have been retreating for almost three decades in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> industrialized countries and experts at an international conference say they still do n't know why. `` There is one less coronary -LRB- heart attack -RRB- every minute in this country,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION>, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have witnessed a significant decrease in heart disease. But the cause of this decline is not clear.'' <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON> said the decline in heart attacks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> started in the 1960s, when the rate of death from cardiac disease was more than 400 per 100,000 persons. The rate is dropping at a steady annual rate and now is about 330 per 100,000 persons. `` It keeps going down and there is no sign of its leveling off,'' <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON> told reporters Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> 2nd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Preventive Cardiology. He said the reasons could be a reduction in smoking, better diets, more exercise or better treatment. But it would take a large, comprehensive study to pinpoint the exact reason for the change. `` The decline in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -LRB- of heart disease deaths -RRB- is extraordinary,'' said Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedewald </PERSON>, associate director for disease prevention at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. `` But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> still has one of the highest rates in the world.'' <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which already has one of the lowest rates of cardiac disease in the world, is also experiencing a decline in death rates. Dr. <PERSON> Hirotsugu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueshima </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardiovascular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said that in 1970 there were 120 cardiac disease deaths annually per 100,000 persons over age 60 in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. That rate now has dropped to 100. For those age 50 to 59, the rate has dropped from 60 per 100,000 in 1970 to 40 at present. `` It is still going down,'' said <PERSON> Ueshima </PERSON>. People in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, he said, are now eating more animal fat, thought to be a risk factor in heart disease, but this has had no apparent impact on rate of heart disease. `` Even though there is more meat -LRB- a source of animal fat -RRB- in the diet, it is still lower than the American diet,'' he said. Japanese get about 25 percent of their calories from fat, compared to about 38 percent in the American diet, he said. Healthier hearts, however, are not universal. A <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> study released at the conference shows deaths among men from heart disease rose steeply between 1970 and 1985 in nearly all of the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> countries where data is available. The study included only industrialized countries and did not include trend data from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> led the rate of reported increase with heart disease death rates shooting up by 62 percent. By comparison, in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> during that same period, the rates declined by 36.5 percent. Even with the increase, however, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> still has a lower rate of heart disease mortality for men, about 297 per 100,000 persons, than the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, the report says. The male heart disease death rate in other countries included increases of 30 percent in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>; 36.9 percent in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>; 42.8 percent in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>; 19.5 percent in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>; 18.1 percent in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, and 14.4 percent in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Deaths among men from heart disease declined throughout western and northern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and also in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. An exception was <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, where the rate increased by 0.8 percent. Except for <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, heart disease death rates declined for women in all of the reported countries. The rates for women declined most remarkably in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, both with drops of about 50 percent. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the death rates for women dropped by 33.8 percent and stood at 119 per 100,000. According to the report, the lowest rate of death due to heart disease was among women in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, where the rate was 41 per 100,000. The highest was among men in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> where the rate was 438 per 100,000.
</TEXT>
