<HEAD>Thornburgh Will Merge Strike Forces Into U.S. Attorneys' Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> says his decision to merge the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s organized crime strike forces into <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys' offices will eliminate confusion and duplication in the current system. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said Monday the 14 strike forces will be abolished and organized crime units will be created in 23 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys' offices around the country by Oct. 1. The plan, which the attorney general earlier said he was considering, has drawn fire from some in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who contend it would blunt an effective weapon against organized crime. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, said in a statement the changes `` are designed to ensure that the department's resources are more comprehensively directed against organized crime. `` They will help reduce confusion and overlapping jurisdiction among federal investigators and prosecutors as well as making more resources available by shutting down duplicate offices,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. Congressional hearings are planned on the issue, including one scheduled today by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Judiciary criminal justice subcommittee. Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, called <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s announcement on the eve of the subcommittee's hearing `` sort of a slap in the face to the many senators and representatives who asked him to wait until we could really discuss this.'' <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> said the subcommittee he chairs has taken no position on the issue but has heard good arguments both for keeping and for abolishing the strike forces. If lawmakers determine <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> made a wrong decision `` we wil