leak reduced. Picks up 8th pvs, `Tveiten said ...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>SVALBARD, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet ocean liner carrying West German tourists rammed an iceberg in the arctic Norwegian sea and was taking on water Tuesday. Many of the more than 900 people aboard abandoned ship, some onto ice floes. The 630-foot <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> radioed north <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s rescue central at 12:27 a.m. that it was listing after hitting an iceberg about 185 miles west of the Norwegian island of <LOCATION> Svalbard </LOCATION>, said a coast guard spokesman. The Soviets and Norwegians said there were no reports of injuries. Most of the passengers were West Germans, many of them elderly. The ship, located east of northern <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>, appeared stable but was taking on water and <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> officials did not know if it would sink, the Norwegian news agency <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> said. The Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the crew had reduced the leak `` and the situation somewhat normalized ... The Maxim Gorky is listing slightly.'' The Norwegian coast guard vessel <PERSON> Senja </PERSON> reached the ship early Tuesday and began rescuing 300 to 400 passengers from lifeboats and from ice floes in near-freezing temperatures and light rain about two miles from the Maxim Gorky. Some 225 people and the crew were said to still be on board. `` The passengers appear to be in good shape and humor ... rescue operations are somewhat difficult because the lifeboats are near the ice, which is moving,'' said <PERSON> Senja </PERSON> captain <PERSON> Kjell </PERSON> <PERSON> Tveiten </PERSON> via the ship's radio. About 575 passengers and 377 crew members were aboard the vessel, the Soviet Merchant Marine Emergency Preparedness office told Norwegian state radio. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> put the total at 953. <PERSON> Tveiten </PERSON> said <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> was listing to starboard and appeared bow-heavy but did not seem to be in immediate danger of sinking. Some passengers had climbed onto thick ice floes to walk to lifeboats and rafts lowered earlier from the damaged ship into the near-freezing waters, reports said. The Norwegian <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said six rescue helicopters were dispatched and would begin carrying passengers to <LOCATION> Svalbard </LOCATION>, about a two-hour flight. Several other Soviet and Norwegian ships were within 300 miles of the distressed ship, which was in international waters. Hospitals in northern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and on the Norwegian islands of <LOCATION> Spitsbergen </LOCATION>, of which <LOCATION> Svalbard </LOCATION> is the largest, were on emergency alert. The <LOCATION> Svalbard </LOCATION> hospital was awaiting Norwegian medical teams dispatched by helicopter, said reports. `` Maxim Gorky'' was built in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1969 and was sold to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1974. In recent summers, the liner has carried mostly West Germans on tours from <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION> arranged by German tour operator <ORGANIZATION> NUR </ORGANIZATION>, news reports said.
