<HEAD>Florida Senate Passes Child-Gun Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved a bill that would jail gun owners who do n't secure their loaded weapons. The action came in response to accidental shootings that killed three children and wounded four this month. `` The nation is watching to see what <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> does,'' Sen. <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Malchon </PERSON>, a co-sponsor of the legislation, said before Monday's 32-4 vote sent the bill to the House. `` It's probably at this point one of the first bills in the nation aimed at safety of children in access to guns,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said. `` It did n't do everything that I wanted it to, but it's a bill that will significantly encourage safety, so I'm very pleased that we passed it.'' A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee was scheduled to consider the bill this morning as the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> began the second day of a three-day special session called by Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>. Accidental gunshots are the fifth-leading cause of death of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> children under age 14, and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> has one of the three highest rates of accidental shootings in the country, according to <PERSON> Malchon </PERSON>, who proposed similar legislation two years ago. Under the bill, adults who fail to secure a loaded weapon that is used by a minor in an accidental shooting could be charged with a felony and sentenced to five years in prison and fined $ 5,000. It would be a misdemeanor if a minor displayed the gun or threatened someone with it. Opponents narrowed the bill's scope by exempting unloaded firearms and guns kept in cars or boats, and dropping the age of minors to under 16 from under 18. Senators also decided to require the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> to come up with a gun safety education plan by next spring rather than adding such a provision to the bill itself. <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> spokeswoman, said the legislation was `` phony, unreal and a disservice to the people of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>.'' She blamed the controversy on the media. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> felt that it needed to do something so that you folks would shut up,'' she told reporters. The House had approved a version of the bill during the regular session, but the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> failed to act on it. In addition to taking up the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> also was scheduled to consider a bill that would punish anyone selling or loaning a weapon to an unsupervised minor without parental permission. The bill also would require gun owners to keep their firearms locked and empty. Another <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> proposal would require gun stores to post signs to warn gunowners about leaving loaded firearms within reach of children. A rash of accidental shootings this month prompted <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> to include the bill in the special session, which originally was called over a $ 2.4 billion turnpike expansion plan. <PERSON> Silvio </PERSON> <PERSON> Claud </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON>, 4, died Saturday a week after he had shot himself at his family's home. The Tampa boy found a .25 - caliber semiautomatic handgun under a couch while his mother was in the His father was not at home. On June 6, a 10-year-old Orlando boy was killed by a playmate. On June 5, an 8-year-old <LOCATION> Miramar </LOCATION> girl was killed by her 10-year-old brother who thought his father's gun was unloaded. Four children, ages 4 to 16, were accidentally wounded this month.
