<HEAD>British Journalist Says China Movement Still Alive</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A British journalist arrested twice for violating Chinese martial law said today that the pro-democracy movement remains alive in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> despite the government's efforts to suppress it. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> made the comments after arriving in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Barron </PERSON>, Asian correspondent for the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities returned his passport Monday after holding it for a week following his second arrest. He was required to write a `` self-criticism'' for violating martial law restrictions on reporting. However, the 49-year-old journalist said he had not been expelled and was free to return to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> any time. He was accompanied by his wife, daughter and three members of his television crew. `` We were free to leave when we liked, and we chose to leave today,'' he said. `` After our holiday, I hope to go back to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and continue reporting.'' On Monday, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> ordered the expulsion of the sixth foreign journalist in 10 days. Given 72 hours to leave was <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>, an American working part-time for the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> Morning News. He was in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on a tourist visa. Last week, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> expelled two Beijing-based <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> correspondents on charges of violating martial law. In addition, three journalists of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, who were not based in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, have been deported. After arriving in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> said he believes the pro-democracy movement, which the government has tried to put down beginning with the military assault in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on June 3-4, still has broad popularity. `` I do n't think the pro-democracy movement in the sense of mass feelings of change has been crushed,'' he told reporters at <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> airport after arriving from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Barron is based in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. `` In fact, when we drove to the airport this morning, we did see a few truckloads of troops, but we also saw at least one individual pass our bus and give the `` V'' sign ... the symbol of the pro-democracy movement. `` We interpreted it as a gesture of defiance ... or support for the pro-democracy movement,'' he said. <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> said he has covered <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> off and on for 15 years. He said he was first detained June 8 while he and his crew were filming a burned-out tank in the capital. He said they were forced to kneel on the road at gunpoint. Their equipment was seized and parts were smashed. His second detention a week ago was entirely different: `` We did self-criticisms, we were not abused in any way, and after three hours of interrogation, we were allowed to go to our hotel.'' Under martial law, foreign reporters are barred from talking to Chinese about martial law or taking pictures of soldiers. Journalists generally have ignored the regulations, however. <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> said he continued reporting after the second arrest, and no effort was made to stop him.
