<DATELINE>NORMAN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oklahoma </ORGANIZATION> coach <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Switzer </PERSON> bid an emotional farewell to college football, ending turmoil over recruiting violations and the arrests of five players on rape, shooting and drug charges. `` I finally decided the time has come for new leadership,'' <PERSON> Switzer </PERSON> said Monday. `` I will never coach at another institution. I will never coach at another college level. I promise you that.'' His resignation ended a 16-year career in which he brought the <ORGANIZATION> Sooners </ORGANIZATION> three national titles and established the fourth best all-time winning percentage. Officials scheduled a news conference today to name a successor. Gov. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellmon </PERSON> issued a statement praising <PERSON> Switzer </PERSON> for posting `` an unparalleled record of success in college football history.'' <PERSON> Switzer </PERSON>, 52, had been under pressure since the school's football program was placed on three years' probation by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collegiate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in December and after five players were charged with felonies. One player was charged with wounding another in a dormitory shooting, three players were charged with raping a woman in a dormitory and one player was charged with conspiracy to distribute cocaine. The state's three largest newspapers and the school's student paper had called for <PERSON> Switzer </PERSON>'s resignation, and the 1949 team canceled a 40-year reunion because of the problems. `` It's no fun anymore. I'm drained. I do n't have the energy level to compete in this arena today,'' said <PERSON> Switzer </PERSON>, who has complained recently about the impact of drugs on college athletics. <PERSON> Switzer </PERSON> also said he was frustrated by <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> rules that do not `` recognize the financial needs of young athletes. `` We have created a system that does not permit me or the program to buy a pair of shoes or a decent coat for a player whose family ca n't afford these basic necessities. `` How can any coach stick to these rules when a young man's father dies many miles away and the son has no money for a plane ticket home to the funeral? <PERSON> Switzer </PERSON> finished with a 157-29-4 record, an .844 winning percentage. His teams won national championships in 1974, 1975 and 1985.
