<SECOND>PM-AMA Convention,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMA Urged to Back Mandatory Cholesterol Labels on Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Food labels would be required to include the product's cholesterol content, caloric value and the specific source of all vegetable oils used under a proposal presented to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The plan, offered by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s annual policymaking convention, also would mandate saturated fat content listings on labels. Cholesterol and such fats have been linked to cardiovascular problems. A related resolution presented Monday asked the association to seek truthful labeling of food products, along with warnings regarding sodium, cholesterol and the additive content of packaged food products. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> would call upon the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to investigate the advertising practices of food manufacturers who present their products as low in sodium or cholesterol under the second plan, submitted by Dr. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfano </PERSON>, a delegate from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abdominal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surgeons </ORGANIZATION>. Both resolutions were referred to an <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> committee that was to vote on whether to recommend that the association's <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> adopt them as policy. A critic said the measures were vague and would provide useless and misleading information to millions of people over age 60 whose cholesterol levels can not be altered by what they eat. But supporters say many other consumers would be well-served by such labeling. `` Health conscious consumers are often misled by the advertising and labeling of common food products such as canned soups labeled as ` low sodium' which contain a substantial sodium content but are only lower in sodium than the manfacturer's regular line of soups,'' <PERSON> Alfano </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> can clear up the confusion by asking the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to assist the consumer by requiring more specific food labeling, he told committee members. Dr. <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Briet </PERSON>, an alternate delegate, presented the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> plan and said he supported <PERSON> Alfano </PERSON>'s resolution. Cholesterol is a waxy substance that can contribute to clogged arteries and heart disease, depending on what type of fatty proteins carry it through the blood. It is produced naturally in the body and develops from eating food with saturated fats or pure cholesterol, such as eggs, butter and animal fat. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has implemented labeling standards that allow foods to be billed as cholesterol-reduced even though they still have large amounts of cholesterol, <PERSON> Briet </PERSON> said. `` Nowhere do they require the source of the oils to be labeled,'' he said. Some plant fats, such as coconut and palm oils, contain high amounts of saturated fatty acids that can help cholesterol form, and food manufacturers like <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> have taken steps to remove such oils from their products. Dr. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mineur </PERSON>, an internist and delegate from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, noted that there is an ongoing debate over so-called `` good'' and `` bad'' cholesterol. He said the proposals would be useless unless they called for labels to differentiate between the two. `` Quit this damn hype'' that all types of cholesterol are bad for everybody, <PERSON> Mineur </PERSON> told the committee. `` Bad'' cholesterol is carried through the bloodstream by low-density lipoproteins linked to the buildup of harmful deposits in the arteries. `` Good'' cholesterol is carried by high-density lipoproteins that researchers believe suck up excess cholesterol in the bloodstream. Furthermore, <PERSON> Mineur </PERSON> argued, reducing cholesterol consumption is only useful for those under age 60. There's no evidence that people older than that can lower their risk of heart disease by altering their intake of fats, he said.
