<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> has officially changed its name in English to the Union of <LOCATION> Myanmar </LOCATION> and renamed the capital of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Yangon </LOCATION>, the state-run Working People's Daily said. Also Monday, the military government tightened controls on political literature and reopened primary schools nationwide, one year after all classrooms were closed in the wake of pro-democracy demonstrations. The government said it would reopen junior high schools, high schools and universities but has not given specific dates. In the law changing <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s name, the nationality _ <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> _ also was changed to <LOCATION> Myanmar </LOCATION>. The word for <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> language are both pronounced <LOCATION> Myanmar </LOCATION>. The names of states, towns and other geographical sites are to be written in English according to the Burmese pronunciation, the law says. <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, for example, is to be written as <LOCATION> Yangon </LOCATION>, which is the Burmese pronunciation of the capital. The military rulers who seized power in September while brutally putting down the popular uprising for democratic reforms had already dropped the term `` <LOCATION> Socialist </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>,'' calling the country the Union of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> in English. The move was an apparent attempt to appease a populace angered by a quarter century of ruinous socialist policies. The latest change in the country's name, government officials say, is to better reflect <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s ethnic diversity. The term <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> connotes <PERSON> Burman </PERSON> _ the dominant race in the country _ to the exclusion of ethnic minorities. Several minority groups have been fighting for greater autonomy from the central government for four decades. The government on Monday increased penalties against violators of a 1962 law on publications, increasing maximum prison terms from three to seven years and fines from $ 320 to $ 4,800 for those who publish material without proper registration. The act says printing presses must be registered with authorities and forbids falsification of facts in declarations by printers and publishers. <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Muang </PERSON>'s military council has promised general elections next year and allowed the formation of opposition political parties, and many of the 200 parties have published anti-government pamphlets without official permission.
