<HEAD>FAA Workers At Some Airports Get Added Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES PLAINES, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal officials say they hope an offer of higher pay will attract and keep air traffic controllers at the nation's busiest towers and control centers. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> announced that 2,100 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> controllers, technicians and safety inspectors at 11 facilities in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> areas will get pay raises of up to 20 percent. `` The air traffic controllers in the busiest centers of this country will be some of the highest paid people in the federal government,'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said Monday at <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> offices near <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, the nation's busiest. `` I've been to those centers and frankly I think those jobs deserve that kind of compensation.'' Many <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> control rooms have been chronically understaffed since former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> fired some 11,400 air traffic controllers during an illegal strike in August 1981. The new plan was criticized as `` a Band-Aid on a hemorrhage'' by <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spickler </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Controller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. He said the raises would cover only a fraction of a nationwide work force of 16,000. The union was certified to represent the nation's 7,000 air traffic controllers in 1987, replacing the <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Controllers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which was decertified after the 1981 strike. `` It will address short-term problems,'' union spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Dresden </PERSON> said of the wage plan. `` We would hope that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> would look at fair compensation for all controllers.'' <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials say the agency has difficulty staffing the 11 facilities with qualified workers because of high living costs, complex operations and other unattractive features. In addition, many workers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> are close to retirement age, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which has been urging higher salaries at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>, applauded the program. `` We believe this action is an encouraging step toward improving <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>'s ability to efficiently handle commercial air traffic at the nation's busiest airport,'' the carrier said. <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials said the program will cost an extra $ 5 million a year from department funds, requiring minor cutbacks in other programs. The 5-year demonstration project will be made permanent if it is successful, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said. Top-level air traffic controllers now make $ 60,000 to $ 65,000 a year, including overtime, before the raises. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said union representatives indicate the program is already working at targeted facilities. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has received a lot of applications for the positions since the program was announced in March, and those applying are highly skilled. The program earlier this year survived attempts by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to restrict it workers at <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> and limit raises to 10 percent of base pay, department officials said. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> facilities affected by the incentive plans include air traffic control centers in <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Ronkonkoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; and the <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> international airport towers and terminal radar approach control facilities. The program also covers approach-control facilities at <LOCATION> Westbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; and flight standards district offices in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Farmingdale </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stream </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Teterboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
