<HEAD>Rain in Southeast; Flash Flood Warnings in Five States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Showers and thunderstorms produced more heavy rain in sections of the <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION>, and flash flood watches remained in effect today for parts of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. About 1 -LCB- inches of rain fell in 45 minutes at <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sterling </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, flooding streets and basements and backing up sewers, and more than three-quarters of an inch fell in an hour at <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>. On Monday, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> farmers moved livestock to higher ground and riverfront homeowners set out sandbags as weather officials warned of more rainfall and the expected cresting of the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tallapoosa </LOCATION> rivers A storm that dumped more than an inch of rain an hour in east <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> flushed creeks across rural roads Monday and forced officials to open rarely used flood gates on <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, Gov. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> toured flood-damaged eastern sections of the state and predicted federal officials would declare the area a disaster. State officials said damage from torrential rains that fell last week was in the millions of dollars. Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered across western portions of the northern Plains. Winds gusted to 60 mph in <LOCATION> Miles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. Thunderstorms erupted Monday night across the eastern slopes of the <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>, where winds gusted to 60 mph at <LOCATION> Vedauwoo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo </LOCATION>. Other thunderstorms were scattered from north-central <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> into the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, and light rain dampened the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>. Intense heat in the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> contributed to the heat stroke death of a 5-year-old girl who became locked in a car trunk in her driveway Sunday as the outdoor temperature climbed to 104 degrees, police said. Authorities said the death appears to be an accident. Today's forecast calls for numerous showers and thunderstorms from the central Gulf Coast through much of the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, and in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and Southeast states; showers and a few thunderstorms scattered from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> across central <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>; and widely scattered showers and thunderstorms mainly in the higher elevations of the northern and central Rockies. Predicted highs: in the 70s and 80s east of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, and from the central and northern coasts of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> across northern <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> to eastern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>; the 60s over the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>; the 90s over the central <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>, the Plains and much of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>; and over 100 degrees in the central Plains, and from the <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> to southwest <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 41 degrees at <LOCATION> Missoula </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, to 93 degrees at <LOCATION> Valentine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>. Other reports: _ East: <ORGANI