<FIRST>r a PM-PhiladelphiatoPhiladelphia     06-20 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philadelphia to Philadelphia,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northerners Head South to Mark Civil Rights Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of Northerners have embarked on a pilgrimage to one of the shrines of the civil rights movement of the 1960s to commemorate the slayings of three young men in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, Miss. A 13-bus convoy carrying about 500 Northerners left here Monday for ceremonies marking the 25th anniversary of the slayings. `` I expect to learn about how they got involved, why they got involved,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, 21, an <ORGANIZATION> Antioch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> student who is working as a summer intern in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> city government. `` It will help us to appreciate what they endured.'' The buses, including three from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, were scheduled to arrive today in <LOCATION> Meridian </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, near the small town of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, where ceremonies Wednesday will honor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON>. The three men were shot to death June 21, 1964, after they had gone to inspect a church burned by the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION>. Their bodies were found 44 days later in an earthen dam. `` It is important to commemorate the sacrifices that were made in the civil rights movement,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON>, 37. The <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, attorney came up with the idea for the convoy last winter after watching the movie `` Mississippi Burning,'' a dramatization of the slayings and the resulting investigation. `` It gives us the opportunity to bring into the consciousness of the whole country the need for a continuing commitment to civil rights,'' <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON> said. Seven men eventually were convicted in federal court of violating the three men's civil rights. Another defendant pleaded guilty, eight were acquitted and the cases against the three others ended in mistrials. Murder charges were dropped in state court. The <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> Project is sponsored by the <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Schwerner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, which is co-chaired in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> by Mayor <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON> and seven others, and in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> by Secretary of State <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Mopus </PERSON>. <PERSON> Goode </PERSON>, the first black mayor of the nation's fifth-largest city, will fly to <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> with about 150 people Wednesday to address a `` commemoration of the past'' at <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, former executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equality </ORGANIZATION>, and members of the victims' families also will speak. The <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> convoy will leave <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> on Thursday as will a south-to-north convoy that will stop in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for meetings with members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and a rally at the Capitol Friday. The convoy will go to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Saturday for a ceremony at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Divine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. Several participants said the trip will provide valuable insight. `` To know where you're going, you've got to know where you came from,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, 67, a curator at the Afro-American Historical and Cultural Museum in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. He said he was struck by the small proportion of whites boarding the buses in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. `` When <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> marched, there was 25 to 30 percent whites,'' he said. `` Here, it's maybe 1 percent. That will give you something to think about. That will give you an idea where the country is headed. I'm not being bitter. I'm just telling you the truth.'' But <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON>, the organizer, said he hoped the trip would demonstrate that the civil rights legacy belongs to all Americans. `` The lessons we intend to present this week are lessons which the country must learn, which is that the price of liberty is eternal vigilance, that the civil rights movement, though it was focusing on the rights of blacks, was an American movement, a patriotic movement.''
</TEXT>
