<HEAD>Guerrillas Say Afghan Government Holding American Photographer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Afghan government forces have seized an American free-lance photographer who was traveling with Moslem guerrillas on assignment for <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, resistance sources say. He is the first American believed captured by Afghans during the civil war. Guerrillas sources identified him Monday as <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, 42, a photographer from <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, N.M. He had been covering the Afghan war based in the <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> frontier city of <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>. The Afghan government did not confirm the arrest immediately. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> cited the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Privacy Act and said they could not comment on such a capture. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> was seized last Wednesday in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the Afghan capital, guerrilla sources in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> said on condition of anonymity. He is being held in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and is reported in good condition, they said. At least three Western correspondents and two foreign aid workers have been captured in the past while traveling with the guerrillas. All were later released unharmed. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> had made several forays into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> with the guerrillas. His photographs have appeared in major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> publications, including <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and Time magazine. `` He had snuck into the country disguised as a Moslem guerrilla. I saw photos of him in that garb,'' said free-lance writer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, who has known <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> for 15 years.
