<HEAD>Supreme Court: Videotape-Testimony Law Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has struck down a law allowing videotaped testimony by child victims of sexual abuse. The court Monday declared the 1987 law unconstitutional because it deprives the accused of the right to confront their accusers at trial. The law, enacted by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> over Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s veto, allows the defense to cross-examine the child witness about the videotaped testimony during the trial but not during the taping itself `` Cross-examination often depends for its effectiveness on the ability of counsel to punch holes in a witness' testimony at just the right time, in just the right way,'' said Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stamos </PERSON>, citing a 1988 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling in a case from <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> is one of several states that have adopted so-called `` child shield'' laws intended to protect young victims of sexual abuse from the trauma of testifying in open court and to minimize their fright and confusion. The law applied only to certain sexual offenses committed against a child 12 or younger, but in declaring it unconstitutional the justices said they were worried it would be expanded to include the elderly or handicapped. In vetoing it, the governor predicted it would be declared unconstitutional. Last year, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> overturned the conviction of an <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> man who was made to testify behind a one-way screen to prevent his accusers from seeing him. He had been found guilty of molesting two 13-year-old girls. The high court said the man's rights to a fair trial and to confront his accusers appeared to have been violated.
