<SECOND>PM-Steel Plant Cleanup,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Steel, Maryland Agree on $92 Million Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to spend $ 92 million over five years to curb toxic releases from a plant that has piled up $ 150,000 in pollution fines over the past year. The agreement, announced Monday, expands on a $ 15.2 million air pollution cleanup promised by the steelmaker in 1987. Officials said that the agreement, the largest ever negotiated by the state with an industrial polluter, is legally binding and that <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> could be fined more than $ 100,000 for failing to maintain the cleanup schedule. <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>'s Sparrows Point complex at <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> employs 8,000 workers and produces steel for ships, bridges, buildings, autos and appliances. The plant is the third-largest source of cancer-causing chemicals in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and one of the state's leading industrial sources of sulfur dioxide emissions, which have taken the principal blame for acid rain. Buoyed by its first profitable year since 1981, <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> pledged in 1987 to reduce emissions. The new agreement calls for more extensive measures, including a $ 40 million modernization of a chemical recovery plant to reduce emissions of sulfur dioxide and toxic pollutants, mainly benzene and hydrogen cyanide. Benzene can cause leukemia and other cancers, anemia and other health problems. Hydrogen cyanide can kill if inhaled in high concentrations. <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> also promised to repair leaking walls and flues at a cost of $ 24 million to cut down on the black smoke belching from three smokestacks. By 1994, the cleanup should result in reductions of 54 percent in particulates, 67 percent in sulfur dioxide, 50 percent in volatile organic compounds that create ozone, and 30 percent in benzene, officials said.
