<HEAD>Federal Magistrate Temporarily Preserves College Corner School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A school that has straddled the <LOCATION> Indiana-Ohio </LOCATION> border for nearly 100 years, a center stripe in the gymnasium marking the state line, must continue to accept students from both states, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> magistrate said. Magistrate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Merz </PERSON> on Monday blocked an attempt by <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> officials to close <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> students and force them to attend another school miles from home. <PERSON> Merz </PERSON>'s preliminary injunction forces the Union County -LRB- Ind. -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to abide by a 1964 court order that bars it from altering operation of the school with the <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corner </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> -RRB- school board without consent of both boards. `` While the joint operation may be cumbersome, it is not impossibly so and has worked for almost 100 years,'' <PERSON> Merz </PERSON> wrote. `` It is needed to provide a school for the children of College Corner. It is needed to uphold the obligation of defendants to obey their own solemn undertakings and the judgment of this court.'' The school was built by the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> districts so that children from either state could attend. Last week, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Amick </PERSON>, superintendent of the <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> corporation, said the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> board has voted to sever its relationship with the <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corner </ORGANIZATION> board because of conflicting state laws that jeopardize state money for <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> students. He also cited a poor relationship with members of the College Corner board. About 280 <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> students attend <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, comprising about 75 percent of the enrollment. College Corner officials say that without the arrangement, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> pupils will be forced to attend school miles away because the community does n't have enough students to operate its own school.
