<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>, faced with increasing civil violence, reimposed a nationwide state of emergency today less than six months after he had lifted it. Foreign and Deputy Defense Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> had proclaimed the state of emergency to try to control unrest that is believed caused by Sinhalese extremists. The emergency, which became effective immediately, is to last for one month and then be extended by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> every month. Emergency regulations give police and the military broad powers to arrest and hold suspects without warrants or other judicial requirements. Authorities also can dispose of bodies without inquests. Sinhalese extremists, mostly belonging to the left-wing <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, are believed to have led a crippling 8-day-old strike by workers of the state-owned public transport company The strike by 20,000 workers of the <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has often turned violent and has forced more than 4,000 buses off the road. `` Public services, including transport, have been paralyzed by forcing the workers to keep away from work,'' <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> said. Strike sponsors have threatened private bus and taxi drivers and last week set ablaze 15 buses, police said. Since it began an anti-government campaign in 1987, the Sinhalese front has been blamed for killing more than 3,500 people, most of whom were government officials or governing party activists. <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON>, without naming the extremists, said more than 1,700 people have been killed since January, of whom 965 were politicians, government officials and policemen. `` There has been progressive escalation of violence, acts of sabotage and disruption of essential services throughout the country,'' he said. `` Under such a situation, the government can not look on inactively.'' The Sinhalese militants launched their anti-government drive to protest peace overtures made to rebels of the Tamil community, who have been fighting for an independent nation since 1983. The insurrection forced <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s predecessor, <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayewardene </PERSON>, to declare a state of emergency in May 1983. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> lifted the emergency on Jan 11, nine days after he took office, in a bid to defuse ethnic tensions. He had pledged it would not be imposed again. The Tamil separatist campaign has claimed 9,000 lives. Tamils say they are discriminated against in jobs and education by the majority <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION>. Tamils, mostly Hindus, form 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. The mainly Buddhist Sinhalese comprise 75 percent and control the government and the military.
