<FIRST>r a AM-YellowstoneExhibit     06-20 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yellowstone Exhibit,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Park Pulls Together a Fire Exhibit to Meet Public Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> has added an exhibit on the devastating fires of 1988, intended to help visitors drive through the park's charred areas _ as well as the unscarred half _ with more understanding. `` I hope people will learn enough to have a choice of what they think,'' said <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Knight </PERSON>, a park naturalist. `` They still might be mad, but that's their choice.'' Knight directed planning and construction of the exhibit, which opened Saturday in the visitors center at <LOCATION> Grant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>. The $ 136,000 production was an unusual crash program for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which usually requires at least two years of planning on a major exhibit, she said. The motivation was an unprecedented public interest, <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> said. `` It was a <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> of forest fires,'' she said. `` It was the first time fire was brought into people's living rooms on a steady basis.'' The exhibit, she said, shows the short-term effects of the fires, from five to 25 years from now, and explores the long-range future of <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>. The causes _ drought, lightning storms, the park's geography _ are explained, as well as recent history of fire supression that contributed to the build-up of fuel. The exhibit includes murals, portraits of firefighters, a video recouting the fury of the fires and presentations about animals. Grant Village survived a seige of fire in late July, although fast-running flames came within feet of staff dormitories. Now the area is an almost surreal scene: blackened trees interspersed with orange lodgepole pines that are dead but still have their needles. Except in the badly charred stands, there is a lush carpet of green grass growing through the soot and ash. And to the north and east, around <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, there is no evidence of the fires that swept through half the 2.2 million acre park. <PERSON> Knight </PERSON>, 44, typifies those who believe the fires were, in historical terms, good for the country's first national park, with long-term benefits for vegetation and wildlife. The exhibit does not, however, address the decision to allow many fires to burn naturally until late July, or refer to disputes between firefighters and park rangers that hampered some efforts to quell the flames until it was too late. `` We're not touching policy,'' said <PERSON> Knight </PERSON>, who has been with the park service for 22 years. `` We're trying to get across that all of <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> is not the same, that it wo n't recover the same.'' The exhibit she coordinated will take most visitors about 20 minutes to tour, although <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> said there is enough information available for extremely interested tourists to spend more than two hours. Design costs ran $ 16,000 and production $ 120,000, <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> said, not including the salaries and overtime required. The exhibit closes with writings by <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, a conservationist who remarked in 1927 that in fire-blackened forests, `` There were some scenes of desolation that pretty nearly drive an unimaginative person crazy.'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> concluded that `` an optimist could go surging through that blackened, misshapened world rejoicing because the forest will look just as beautiful as before _ in two or three centuries.'' Knight, like most other park employees, takes <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>'s view. `` It's always a changing park,'' she said. `` It was n't the same park in 1988 as it was in 1953 when I first saw it. `` The difference, obviously, is that this change is much more dramatic.''
