<HEAD>The Price of Pluralism: Cleaning Up From Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With an exuberance matched only by the novelty of their new democratic parliamentary elections, Poles plastered campaign posters across the country over the last month. Now the time has come to pay the price of pluralism: cleaning up. With the signs of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s fledgling venture into free elections looking a bit tattered, the question remains: Who should scrub, scrape and wash away the campaign posters, and who should pay for it? An estimated 700,000 posters went up in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> alone in an astounding display of uncensored campaigning unseen in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> during 45 years of communist rule. That represented about 40 tons of paper, a significant amount in a country where university students sometimes do n't have anything suitable on which to type their theses. Most of the posters came from the independent Solidarity movement, which went on to win all but one of the 261 seats available to opposition candidates and hand the government a stinging rebuke in two rounds of voting that started June 4 and ended Sunday. Now, however, the posters such as those featuring gallant <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> in cowboy gear and a Solidarity button that says, `` High noon is June 4,'' are peeling off apartment block walls. Rain has smeared the sentiments of support for a communist coalition candidate whose banner hung along a main city thoroughfare. `` The emotions subsided, the litter remained ... Who is going to clean it up?'' asked the daily Solidarity newspaper. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON>, head of the Solidarity campaign in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, promised in the article that the union would work on the cleanup with city authorities. `` But we do not have the money to hire people. We have only debts,'' <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON> said. `` So those who were putting up the posters for free now will to clean them off, too.'' Another issue of the newspaper carried a call from 12-year-old <PERSON> Mikolaj </PERSON> <PERSON> Bober </PERSON>, who put up posters all over the Zoliborz section of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. `` We have to clean it up,'' he said. `` I am eager to do this ... and I count on the help of other boys and girls.'' The director of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> municipal cleaning enterprise, <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Swierczynski </PERSON>, said the city will clean the sites it administers, but building janitors, the bus and tramway services and others will have to take care of their areas. `` There is quite a lot to do ... and the whole -LRB- cleanup -RRB- campaign will surely take a lot of extra money,'' said <PERSON> Swierczynski </PERSON>, making it clear that the expenses of Western-style electioneering were not anticipated in his department's budget. `` The scale of the poster phenomenon in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> is extraordinary,'' he added.
