<FIRST>r w AM-Solstice     06-20 0115</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solstice,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solstice Marks Longest Day of the Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wednesday is the summer solstice, the longest day of the year in the Northern Hemisphere. The solstice occurs at 5:53 a.m. EDT, according to astronomers at the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Observatory here. The moment marks the time during the summer when the sun is farthest from the equator. The date, known in folklore as Midsummer, had been a time for parties and frivolity to celebrate the season. Listing the date as the start of summer has become a popular convention among calendar makers in recent years, but the designation carries no official weight. Meteorologists, for example, consider summer to have begun June 1.
</TEXT>
