<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Child care will be a significant issue in the 1990 congressional campaign and Republican chances could be damaged if child care and parental-leave legislation is vetoed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic political strategists said Tuesday. <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON>, a Republican consultant who was pollster for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign in 1988 and is a former director of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> campaign committee, said: `` I do n't believe serious political candidates in 1990 can avoid discussing the issue of child care. I do n't believe they can avoid discussing the issue of long-term health care.'' <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON> said he did not believe parental leave would be an issue because `` in terms of an issue you have to have clear-cut differences. It is very hard for me to imagine two candidates going at each other over the issue of parental leave.'' <PERSON> Celinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Lake </PERSON>, a Democratic consultant, argued that `` work and family issues,'' including child care, parental leave and long-term health care, `` have emerged as major policy issues in 1990.'' `` The president has vetoed the minimum wage,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> said. `` There is some possibility of a veto of parental leave and child care. If those three vetos come down, that is a definite statement of the Republicans' position on work and family issues, and it is up to the Democrats to take those voting records into the district and make those the issues that decide elections.'' The two consultants appeared on a panel sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION>, the Great American Family Tour, and Lifetime television, which discussed results of a poll published by several magazines in February in which 74 percent of those responding said family issues should be a top priority for the president and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON>, asked by a member of the audience about the effects of a series of presidential vetos, said, `` I think any time you are seen as a naysayer, that you have nothing positive to offer in the debate, you have a problem with voters of either gender.'' `` If programs have particular importance to women and you are vetoing a series of programs ... I think the cumulative effect of that could have more impact than, say, a single program and certainly that is one thing we would be watching,'' he said. <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON> said the most recent <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> poll indicates about 5 to 6 percent more support for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s child care program, based on a tax credit, than for a program being considered in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that would involve direct government funding. `` So far, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is doing pretty well with women,'' he said. `` The numbers look very good. Now, if there is a whole series of vetos on legislation that is of particular importance to women, that could be a different ball game.''
