<HEAD>For Passengers on Soviet Ship, It Was Vodka Among the Rocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Ship, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The last thing <PERSON> Rudolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> expected to be served for breakfast on his arctic cruise was vodka. <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> had gone to bed early Monday night, leaving his wife to enjoy a cabaret evening aboard the Soviet cruise liner Maxim Gorky. He ended up spending five hours in a lifeboat floating among icebergs. `` I was in bed when suddenly there was a terrible crash that almost shook me out of bed,'' said <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON>, one of more than 950 passengers and crew aboard the vessel when it struck an iceberg. Obeying instructions from the ship's loudspeakers, the 67-year-old West German pensioner with a walking disability pulled on his trousers, put on his life vest and went on deck to stand by a lifeboat. The liner, on a cruise out of <LOCATION> Bremerhaven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, struck the iceberg about 300 miles east of northern <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION>. No injuries were reported. `` We are all safe and sound here,'' <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from a church on the Norwegian island of <LOCATION> Svalbard </LOCATION>, where passengers were taken by ship and helicopter after the accident. <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> said he had just heard that his wife was safe and coming to join him. They were being taken home to <LOCATION> Wiesbaden </LOCATION> as soon as the rescue operation was complete, he said. He seemed in good spirits, joking: `` I'm standing here in my pajamas, and the trousers keep wanting to fall down to my knees.'' For a while, though, there was nothing to laugh about. `` When I got up on deck, I saw enormous ice blocks around. We were told to get into the lifeboats,'' he said, adding that there was no panic. `` We sat for five hours among the icebergs. The atmosphere was calm, and the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> sailors did everything they could. They gave us vodka and whiskey in the boats, since it was cold,'' said <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON>. `` And blankets too.'' Temperatures in the area were about 38 degrees. `` From the lifeboats, we could see that a third of the ship was under water,'' he said. <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> said that the ship appeared to be moving fast through the icy waters before the crash. There was a slight fog, but not enough to impair vision, he said. The Norwegian coast guard vessel <PERSON> Senja </PERSON> reached the stricken ship early Tuesday and picked up hundreds of passengers who had jumped into lifeboats or scrambled onto ice floes, said <PERSON> Kjell </PERSON> <PERSON> Larssen </PERSON> of the north <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> Rescue Center at <LOCATION> Bodoe </LOCATION>. Others were rescued by helicopter from the ship or ice floes. `` My wife will get here in a while,'' he said. `` They've gotten blankets and stuff together so that people can spend the night, I suppose.''
