<HEAD>Public TV Station Airs Surgery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with rating, telephone calls. PICKS
UP 6ath graf pvs, `Dr. Richard ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman underwent back surgery on live TV and said she agreed to it in hopes of helping others who may need the operation. `` I do n't feel invaded at all,'' said <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Arizin </PERSON>, 27, a sales representative from <LOCATION> Haddonfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, who had suffered from back pain for more than half her life. The surgery took place on public television Monday night. The 2 -LCB- - hour operation to help correct a 50-degree curvature of Mrs. <PERSON> Arizin </PERSON>'s spine is expected to make the 5-foot-9-inch patient an inch and a half taller `` It's really kind of surprising, but the focus is the surgery and the new technique and how it can help other patients,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Arizin </PERSON> said. `` I agreed in the hope that it would help other people who are going through the same thing.'' <ORGANIZATION> WHYY </ORGANIZATION> said it broadcast the operation live for its impact and educational value. `` It's more exciting. It's more television, more immediate. It's just much more real We did it as an attempt to show people what it's really like, without editing,'' said station manager <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Othmer </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> WHYY </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> today said the station received at least 330 calls, its highest ever for one show. She said viewers called the program `` absolutely breathtaking'' and `` magnificent,'' but several found it gory. Ms. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> said the show received a good 6.9 rating and an 11 percent share against the network lineup, which began at 8 p.m. with `` Kate & amp; <PERSON> Allie </PERSON>'' on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, `` ALF'' on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and `` MacGyver'' in <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. The rating is percentage of all homes with television, the share a percentage of televisions in use. Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON>, founder of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Rothman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> for orthopedic surgery, was host during the operation at the hospital. `` It was a tense evening because of the live television, but everything went extremely well,'' <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON> said. `` This is real life, that's what makes this operation so interesting. We do it every day, and even we are impressed.'' Viewers saw Mrs. <PERSON> Arizin </PERSON>, who was introduced in taped sequences, lying on her stomach on the operating table, surgical drapes covering her from the shoulders up and the hips down. Three cameras, including an overhead one, covered the 10-member medical team at work in the two-hour, 20-minute program. Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Balderston </PERSON> performed the operation, during which stainless steel rods were attached to the vertebrae to nearly straighten Mrs. <PERSON> Arizin </PERSON>'s spine. Bone was then grafted onto the rods to hold them in place. `` The surgery used to take six to seven hours. It now takes two to four hours,'' <PERSON> Balderston </PERSON> said. `` Patients used to be in bed for as long as six months. Now they're out of bed in one or two days. They used to be in a plaster body cast for as long as a year. Now it's very unusual to need a cast.'' Two percent of Americans suffer from curvature of the spine, or scoliosis.
