<HEAD>Criticizes Gorbachev, Supports Reform in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> on Tuesday endorsed the `` potential revolution'' under way in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> but criticized President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for not taking a strong stand against suppression of reform in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, in a prepared statement to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, reigstered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for reform throughout the communist world. Whether in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> or in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, he said, reform `` is very much in our interests.'' At the same time, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said no one could predict the outcome of the changes taking place in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and elsewhere. `` In the end,'' he said, `` we do know that the success of reform will depend primarily upon choices made in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, not <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>.'' He stressed, however, that political and economic reform were necessary in order for the East to progress. `` To stand in the way of such necessary, historic change _ as we are seeing to our outrage and sorrow in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ is to turn one's back to the future And that is why General Secretary <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s temporizing comments on those tragic events are disappointing,'' he said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> apparently referred to a statement by the Soviet leader last week that he did not have `` sufficient information'' on events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to make a `` balanced and responsible judgment'' about <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s actions. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> appeared before the committee mostly to report on his meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last month with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and on the summit President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> held in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> at the end of the month with the leaders of the 15 other <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> nations. There <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> outlined a proposal for reductions in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact conventional troops and armories in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and delayed consideration of deploying more powerful short-range nuclear missiles in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told the committee the administration was `` exploring and establishing new vehicles'' to foster cooperation with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` We're actively engaging <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with our eyes open and fixed on our longstanding goals and interests,'' he said. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said these goals were to protect Western security and to promote democratic values and interests. `` The movement we're seeing in Soviet politics presents a potential revolution _ a revolution we hope will succeed,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. In reviewing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee, he endorsed reform in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
