<FIRST>r i AM-France-Prison     06-20 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Prison,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marie Antoinette's Prison Restored To Gloomy Grandeur</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Conciergerie, the dank and forbidding stone prison where victims of the French Revolution spent their final moments, opened to the public Tuesday in all its former gloom and grandeur. Queen <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoinette </PERSON> occupied a cell on the ground floor for 10 weeks in 1793, hoping her supporters would come up with enough money to buy her freedom. She waited in vain, and went to her death at the guillotine on Oct. 16, 1793. The cell she shared with her jailer later was turned into a chapel as a shrine to her memory, but a replica of the cell has been recreated nearby and is decorated with wallpaper embossed with the royal blue and gold lily emblems that covered the walls 200 years ago. <PERSON> Maximilien </PERSON> <PERSON> Robespierre </PERSON>, who sent thousands of heads rolling during his 12-month Reign of Terror against counterrevolutionaries, spent his final hours a few cells away on July 28, 1794. `` His death warrant arrived about 10 a.m., and he was carted away to the guillotine in mid-afternoon,'' <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Colardelle </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Culture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said during a tour of the restored landmark overlooking the Seine. The spot is marked by a simple black marble plaque. Admirers of <LOCATION> Robespierre </LOCATION>, known as the Incorruptible, say history has not done him justice. `` He has been made to bear all the guilt of the Terror,'' said former Health Minister <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartzenberg </PERSON>, one of several public figures eager to rehabilitate <PERSON> Robespierre </PERSON>'s memory. `` All revolutions are characterized by excess of some sort, otherwise they would not be revolutions,'' he said. No one, however, can accuse the French of not paying tribute to <LOCATION> Robespierre </LOCATION>'s victims and others who died during the turbulent events. A small room on the second floor is devoted entirely to their memory. Its four walls are covered with framed lists, in alphabetical order, of the 2,780 aristocrats, gardeners, shoemakers, doctors and clergymen found guilty by the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribunal </ORGANIZATION> and beheaded within three days. The verdict was either guilty or acquittal. There were no appeals. Some names are familiar, like <PERSON> Charlotte </PERSON> <PERSON> Corday </PERSON>, who stabbed <PERSON> Jean-Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Marat </PERSON> in his bath. Others, like <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON>, gardener, are not. A short film with English subtitles helps visitors follow the events and depicts daily life at the prison. Ordinary prisoners shared the squalor of cold cells littered with filthy straw. The wealthy bought their way into cells furnished with beds and sometimes even desks, where many an aristocrat penned his memoirs. Also recreated are the quarters where the condemned were taken to have their shirts ripped wide and the napes of their necks shaved so the guillotine's blade would cut cleanly. Prisoners were allowed to circulate freely during the day in the women's courtyard. Despite their predicament, many privileged ladies managed to keep up with fashion trends, and even groomed themselves without the help of maids. `` <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoinette </PERSON>, in her final days, even learned to put up her own hair,'' said <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Chalon </PERSON>, author of a recent biography. The $ 375,000 renovation of the Conciergerie is one of several refurbishing projects linked to bicentennial celebrations.
</TEXT>
