<FIRST>r e AM-APArts:Rivkin 1stLd-Writethru   06-20 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Rivkin, 1st Ld - Writethru,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Producer Has Singular Priority</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name of group in 1st graf to Fine Young Cannibals,
sted Five</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivkin </PERSON> has produced hit albums for <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>, Fine Young Cannibals and <PERSON> Jody </PERSON> <PERSON> Watley </PERSON>, but the <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> native has `` higher'' priorities. `` In the back of my mind, I always go for the single,'' said the producer of <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>'s `` Kiss,'' <PERSON> Watley </PERSON>'s `` Looking for a New Love'' and Fine Young Cannibals' `` She Drives Me Crazy,'' all No. 1 smashes. `` I go for the throat, really. I really am a singles-oriented person. It's really the way I want to go after it.'' Like a baseball manager who must cope with the personalities of different players, <PERSON> Rivkin </PERSON> _ known in the business as <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Z </PERSON> _ adjusts his style to fit the artist. With Prince, a gifted songwriter and arranger, the producer sees himself as a collaborator and occasional mind reader. `` He's a different personality every day, so you just have to capture whatever personality he is that day. I just think about how to frame whatever mindset he's in.'' With <PERSON> Tyka </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>'s introverted sister, <PERSON> Rivkin </PERSON> took a more delicate approach. He remembered the Jets' first album as his most difficult. `` It was the first real time we discovered a new artrist and we had to come through with all the songs and vocals. We were shooting in the dark, we were taking kids from a bar band and trying to make a national product,'' <PERSON> Rivkin </PERSON> said. `` We had to establish a direction. That was a bit difficult. We had to do every vocal; there was no sampling. Somes things you take for granted now.'' <PERSON> Rivkin </PERSON> was once a musician himself, playing guitar for <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> and writing with country-rock artist <PERSON> Gram </PERSON> <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON>. He had lived in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in the early 1970s, but returned to his hometown in 1974. He was soon behind the control board. `` I did n't want to do it at the time, but I realized I had much more control over material sitting behind that seat. I gave up the idea of being a rock star.'' In 1980, he engineered <ORGANIZATION> Lipps </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s No. 1 dance hit, `` Funkytown,'' and played guitar on their album. He has since produced a remarkable range of acts, from the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> funk of <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, to the blue-eyed soul of <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Oates </PERSON> and <PERSON> Boy </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, to the dance music of <PERSON> Watley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jermaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` I try to fill the holes the artists ca n't fill,'' he said. `` That comes from doing the right sound, a special snare drum sound, a special vocal echo, and from making the artists feel good enough to bring out their personality.'' His sheer diversity has had drawbacks. In an industry that loves labels and openly categorizes music according to race, it's hard to define a white kid from the Midwest who produces best-selling dance records by black artists. `` I used to be classified as an R & amp; B producer. It was a hard notch to get out of. Because I was white, I would get a lot of flack. I've had a lot of No 1 black records. In the face of all that, my own inclination was to combine rock and R & amp; B.'' <PERSON> Rivkin </PERSON> compared himself to in a way to <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON>, speaking of the cameo appearances that were the great film director's trademark A guitar riff is <PERSON> Rivkin </PERSON>'s subtle way of popping up in his work. `` I think if you look real hard, there's a thread running through all those records,'' he said. `` Rhythmically, there's a certain sound. `` In ` Kiss,' it's a major part of the record. Sometimes, it appears as a little wink.'' His presence is unmistakeable in the studio. Hit singles do n't come easy and <PERSON> Rivkin </PERSON> pushes hard for the best sound `` I make singers breath and emote a lot more than they would normally. I always look for that sexy breath. There's a fine line between getting it perfect and not losing the artist when you're doing it I do n't care if there's some rough edges,'' he said. `` Finding a producer is like finding a wife. It's tough. It's a chemistry thing. I like to get involved from the ground up. Usually, what I do is start programming drum parts at home on my machine. If you get a good drum and bass part, that's 90 percent of the pop record.''
