<HEAD>Winery Brothers Win Right to Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Winemakers <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> today won exclusive rights to the family name, thwarting a younger brother who had put his name on a brand of cheese. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> ruled that <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>'s use of his full name on cheese was calculated to mislead consumers into thinking the brand is connected with the E & amp; J Gallo Winery. The judge ordered <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> to quit using his name on cheese. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> has no direct connection with the <LOCATION> Modesto </LOCATION>, Calif.-based Gallo Winery, the world's largest, but sells grapes to his older brothers <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, said he will recommend an appeal. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said at trial in December that he knew of no case in which a person was prohibited from using his full name on a non-competing product. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> claimed in a 1986 lawsuit that they had contracted with a company to market cheese under the <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> name. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, attorney for the winery, contended that <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> was `` riding on the recognition and riding on the power that the <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> mark conferred.'' Previously, a federal judge threw out a countersuit in which <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>, 69, claimed he is entitled to one-third of the winery holdings on grounds that it developed from the estate of the <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> brothers' parents. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON>, now 80, and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON>, now 78, began making wine in 1933, shortly after their father killed their mother, then committed suicide, their attorney said.
