<HEAD>Glenn Urges Cheney to Suspend B-2, Reinstate Osprey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Democratic member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday urged <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> to suspend production of the B-2 stealth bomber because the aircraft has yet to undergo flight testing. <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> in response reaffirmed his support for the B-2, which at $ 500 million a copy is the most expensive plane in history. The bomber is a necessary component of the triad of air -, land - and sea-based nuclear weapons, said <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION>'s Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, a former astronaut and test pilot, argued that pursuing production of the radar-evading plane violates the rule of `` fly before buy.'' The bomber program has been `` buy it, and then we'll see how it flies,'' <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said in a letter to <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION>. `` The B-2 is a total departure from our usual new aircraft,'' <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said. said. `` It is a flying wing. There are new control concepts, different center of gravity considerations, and new aerodynamics just to name a few. Going ahead with additional production before flight tests have even started just does n't make sense.'' <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> has proposed pushing back production of the stealth bomber a year to 1993 and cutting almost $ 4.1 billion from fiscal 1990 and 1991 budgets for the plane. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said $ 22.4 billion has already been invested in the stealth program, and concluded that it would be `` totally irresponsible'' to continue production without flight test results. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> argued that the money earmarked for the stealth bomber could be used for `` high-priority conventional programs that have been terminated or deferred.'' <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION>, said he favors the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>' V-22 Osprey, a battlefield aircraft designed to take off like a helicopter and fly like an airplane. The Pentagon had hoped to spend $ 25.9 billion on 663 Ospreys, including $ 1.3 billion in 1990, but <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> decided to terminate the program. <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> is `` a big believer in the triad, and he thinks the B-2's long-range capabilities and its stealth capacities make it an important strategic asset to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> `` So, he plans to continue right on with that and he reaffirmed his strong support for the B-2 program.''
