<HEAD>Dieter Sheds 173 Pounds, Donates Excess 4 Square Feet of Skin to
Burn Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dieters who lose 10 or 20 pounds may give away their baggy old clothes. But <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Genz </PERSON>'s 173-pound loss left him with too much skin, so he donated about 4 square feet to help save burn victims. `` This is a first for us. ... Occasionally, rarely, if a child is a patient a parent may donate skin,'' <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Perls </PERSON>, director of education for the <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. The 5-foot-11 Genz, 43, weighed 430 pounds last August when he began a high-protein weight-loss regimen. Last week, he weighed in at 260 and prepared for surgery to remove excess skin from his abdomen to ease back pains and other problems. `` I was sitting at lunch with some nurses and we were joking that it was too bad I could n't donate the skin,'' said <PERSON> Genz </PERSON>, equipment coordinator for the emergency department at <LOCATION> Sherman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Elgin </LOCATION>, just northwest of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` Then one of the nurses said, ` Why not?''' he recalled Tuesday from his hospital bed, where he was recovering from Monday's surgery. The decision `` left me with a good feeling,'' <PERSON> Genz </PERSON> said, adding that he felt fine but had `` kind of a big scar.'' `` I've worked in emergency rooms for 25 years. ... I'm a strong supporter of transplants,'' he said. What if he gains back the lost weight? `` The skin would just stretch out again _ but I do n't intend to gain the weight back,'' <PERSON> Genz </PERSON> said. The operation removed 19 -LCB- pounds of skin and adjoining tissue, <PERSON> Genz </PERSON> said. His donated skin _ about four square feet _ will be used to care for burn patients at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` More lives are saved by skin transplants than any other donated organ,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Gottlieb </PERSON>, professor of surgery and director of the university's burn unit. `` What kills burn patients is loss of fluid and infection,'' Ms. <PERSON> Perls </PERSON> said. Donated skin `` is used as a kind of living bandage'' while the patient regenerates his own skin, she said. Then the borrowed tissue sloughs off. Because its use is temporary, skin used for burn patients need not be a perfect tissue type match like that used for skin grafts or other organ transplants, Ms. <PERSON> Perls </PERSON> said. She noted that noting most such tissue is removed from cadavers. But while <PERSON> Getz </PERSON>'s contribution is unusual, `` this kind of weight loss is unusual, too,'' she said. `` Anything that will make people think about organ or tissue donation is good,'' she said. University hospital spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Easton </PERSON> agreed. `` There's a shortage of any sort of donated organ. ... It is beneficial and it comes at a good time _ I think they're planning to use some of it today,'' <PERSON> Easton </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Genz </PERSON>'s contribution. `` I think any sort of organ donation ... is a valuable, life-saving procedure.''
