<HEAD>Visa Applications Drop as New Exit Control Takes Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New controls on Chinese travel abroad took effect Tuesday, causing the number of applicants for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> visas to plummet. Dozens of Chinese had camped outside the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Canadian embassies in hopes of getting their visa applications in before the new rules took effect. Among them were doctors, computer scientists and economists, some of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s best-educated and brightest citizens, all hoping to study or do research abroad. `` We did n't dare leave to eat or sleep for fear of losing our place in line,'' said an economist who succeeded in applying at the <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> and was waiting outside for a response. The revised visa requirements appeared designed to screen depatures more carefully and prevent fugitive dissidents from getting out. They came two weeks after the army rolled into <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and opened fired on students and supporters demanding a freer society. There was much confusion about the new regulations. Under existing procedure, Chinese are required to obtain exit permits from their local police stations before Chinese guards outside foreign embassies allow them to enter to apply for visas. According to reports in the official media over the weekend, the new rules invalidate all permits issued before Tuesday. Through Monday, Chinese could still use the old permits to enter embassy grounds, but as of Tuesday the old permits were not good for even that. One radio report and a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> source said visa applicants now must also get a second permit after obtaining the visa. Many Chinese applicants and several Western consular officials said they did not know about this requirement and it could not immediately be confirmed. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said only three Chinese showed up at the consulate Tuesday with the new permit and were allowed by Chinese guards to apply for visas. By comparison, 350 people applied on Monday, about average for summertime, he said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> are two of the most popular destinations for Chinese traveling abroad for business or study. A third popular country, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, has not reopened its consular section since closing it after the military crackdown began on June 3. Most of those waiting outside the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Canadian embassies on Tuesday made plans to go abroad before the crackdown and were not involved in the protests. But they said they feared police would be stingy about issuing exit permits in the new conservative political climate. `` I have n't been in trouble but -LRB- <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> officials -RRB- may be worried about ` spiritual pollution,''' said a doctor waiting for a response to his wife's application to study in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Chinese officials refer to unwanted Western cultural influences and values as spiritual pollution.
