<HEAD>Bush Moving on Soviet Policy After Four Months of Study</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is seeking to take advantage of new openness in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> as he forges a Soviet policy designed to meld <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> into the international community. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is on the move now, unveiling new arms negotiating tactics as well as plans to relax financial strictures on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> as that Soviet-bloc nation moves toward democracy. But four months of silence at the beginning of the administration, while the president and his aides conducted a `` strategic review,'' left the impression that the new team was uncertain how to deal with a volcano of Soviet reform. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> staff member for Soviet and <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> affairs, and other <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides are seeking to counter that impression. `` We know where we want to go,'' <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON> said. `` We know of the enormous opportunities that are out there. And we also understand that if one makes a mistake in an era of transition, that there is no inevitability for stability in international order, and it could have a very high price.'' `` We are trying to create the structure of a relationship that makes it less likely it can be reversed, less likely that we can have a return to the sort of conflict we saw in the 1970s and 80s. And finally, to integrate the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> into the international system so that it uses its enormous power to solve international problems rather than to exploit them,'' <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON> said in a speech Tuesday at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, during a summit of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> three weeks ago, outlined a plan to rapidly reduce superpower conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, surpassing even the proposals of Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Some of the fine print of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s Soviet-bloc plans, outlined in broad terms over the past two months, has been disclosed recently concerning arms negotiating tactics and help for the Polish economy. Within a few days, said <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON>, the administration will divulge specifics of new proposals in the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reduction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Talks </ORGANIZATION> to test _ with the Soviets _ means of verifying the reduction or elimination of long-range nuclear weapons. The ideas take advantage of apparent new Soviet openness to verification and are designed to avoid the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> misgivings that helped block ratification of the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> in 1979 and held up the Intermediate-range Nuclear Force Treaty last year, said <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON>. `` The purpose of the confidence-building and verification measures which ... are being conveyed to the Soviets are to accelerate, not delay, a historic agreement,'' said <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON>, declining to specify whether the proposals envision on-site inspections or satellite surveillance. More details of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s policy toward <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are expected early next month when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> travels to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, two Soviet bloc nations that <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON> said are pushing away `` the dead hand of communism'' with their political and economic reforms. `` Some believe that in trying to conceptualize a Soviet-American relationship through the end of the century, taking four months to do that, is a long time. I do n't how long they take to buy a house,'' <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON> said. `` We have to keep remembering that dealing with an autocratic system as exists in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, that reversibility is possible. We have just seen tragic evidence of that fact in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON>, referring to the suppression of the pro-democracy movement in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, in which thousands reportedly died. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his top aides have lived most of their adult lives during the Cold War. <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON> and his boss, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adviser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scowcroft </ORGANIZATION>, also served in the White House during detente, under Presidents <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, when many proclaimed the end to the Cold War. And so they dilute their hope with caution. `` I wrote myself the toast that President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> gave in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> indicating that detente was irreversible'' in the early 1970's, said <PERSON> Blackwill </PERSON>. `` It turned out that that was n't so.'' `` The danger still exists. ... The Cold War began in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and it must end there,'' he said, adding that Soviet military intervention in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> now `` would set back normalization of East-West relations through the end of the century.'' `` It is somewhat difficult for me to imagine that the Cold War is over when today, there are 580,000 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` After Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s unilateral reductions, which we welcome, which were announced at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> last December, there will still be 550,000 men of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. We have a ways to go before the Cold War is over in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.''
