<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They were in hog heaven over at the World Pork Expo. There was everything a porker could produce: pork rinds, pork chops and just plain pork. There was even stuff to help farmers produce plumper profits. `` It's so hot it's going to smoke your hair,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Yan </PERSON> said as he stirred spicy fried pork and promoted his cookbook. `` God bless you and all the pigs in the world. Let's all have one pork dish a day for the next 365 days.'' About 75,000 people went hog wild at the second annual Expo, a three-day pork fest that ended Tuesday. Browsers sampled the latest pork products and hog farmers examined equipment and research aimed at improving profits. `` I enjoyed the Chinese cooking demonstration,'' said <PERSON> Bobbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Angstrom </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, who accompanied her husband to the show. `` I'm glad I did n't go to the shopping mall.'' At a booth operated by <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Connor </PERSON> popped pork rinds into hot oil and cooked them into the snack President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is said to enjoy. Visitors sampled the rinds _ pieces of hogs' skin _ plain and with barbecue sauce and cheese. `` The acceptance of this product since <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> became president has been incredible,'' said <PERSON> Connor </PERSON>, whose company's sales are up 12 percent over 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Elanco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION>, which manufactures medications for livestock, set up supermarket meat cases to display pork products, and demonstrated how the meat is cut and trimmed. `` The trend now is convenience food,'' said <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Buller </PERSON> of <PERSON> Elanco </PERSON>, holding a flat plastic pack with four strips of bacon. `` Here is a big one _ microwave bacon. The pad in there soaks up the grease.'' <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Etzler </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Pork </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> offered information on how hogs can be bred to contain less fat, as well as ideas for cooking pork. `` Our main message is that we have a leaner product, and that pork will work in a well-balanced diet,'' <PERSON> Etzler </PERSON> said. `` I think we're changing people's attitudes, but not as fast as we'd like.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Gasparro </PERSON>'s artwork is worth a fortune, but people drop it on the ground every day one cent at a time and few bother to pick it up. For sentimental reasons, <PERSON> Gasparro </PERSON> usually fetches pennies from the sidewalk. <PERSON> Gasparro </PERSON> designed the tails side of the penny that replaced the wheat-back penny 30 years ago. His initials can be found just to the right of the Lincoln Memorial's base. Occassionally when he gets a penny in change, he'll point out his work to the cashier. `` They think I'm goofy,'' the former chief engraver of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said. `` I'll say, ` I designed it, you can see my initials if you've got good eyesight.''' As the man who designed the <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> dollar, he is the only living person to have sculpted the front and back of a general-circulation <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> coin. He also designed the back of the <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> half dollar. <PERSON> Gasparro </PERSON>, who asked a reporter not to write his age, said he is dissappointed the <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> dollar was n't more popular. He figures people just could n't get used to a dollar that does n't fold. But the back of the penny, which he designed in 1958 and was first issued in 1959 to mark the 150th anniversary of <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>'s birth, is the most circulated of his work When he presented his design to his superiors, they told him to remove the words `` Lincoln Memorial'' from below the relief of the building and 13 stars that ran around the outer edge of the coin. <PERSON> Gasparro </PERSON> agreed, but refused to take out his initials and the tiny statue of <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> between the sixth and seventh columns, two features his boss said would look like smudges of dirt. `` If you do that, it would look like a library,'' he recalled saying at the time. After 38 years at the mint, <PERSON> Gasparro </PERSON> retired in 1981 and has been sculpting about 15 to 20 commemorative coins a year for private groups.
