<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, in a rare moment of candor about his personal life, said Tuesday he was so determined to come to <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1935 that he lied to get around British restrictions. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> applied and was accepted at the <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jerusalem </ORGANIZATION> that year even though he had no plans to study. The acceptance paved the way for an entry permit from the British. `` I decided that this was the only way,'' he said. The Polish-born <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, who was leader of a militant Jewish underground and later a senior officer in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mossad </LOCATION> intelligence service, usually is tight-lipped about his personal life. He was speaking to about 600 Israelis who were among 2,000 Jews saved from the Nazi Holocaust with the help of acceptance certificates from the university between 1932 and 1941. Many applicants used the certificates to get around immigration restrictions, said university spokesman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrach </PERSON>. The university was trying to save as many people as possible, but had to limit the number of certificates because it was being closely watched by the British, <PERSON> Barrach </PERSON> said. In his 1935 application, the 20-year-old <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> wrote he had studied law for a year at <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> to please his parents, but that Hebrew literature was his true love. `` After some months of study, it became clear to me that the only place where I could fully realize my desires and exercise my abilities would be the Institute for Jewish Studies at the <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>,'' wrote <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, then known as <PERSON> Icko </PERSON> <PERSON> Yezernicki </PERSON>. He also wrote that his family was well-off and would support him. The letter `` was n't too accurate a description of my feelings,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> conceded Tuesday. `` I had to put my family into debt to be able to immigrate.'' He said he spent some of his first days in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> wandering around campus and sitting in the library. `` I wanted to study, also Hebrew literature, but I could n't because I had nothing to live on,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> told reporters, adding with a smile: `` In the meantime, I got involved in other things. They included joining <ORGANIZATION> Irgun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zvi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leumi </ORGANIZATION>, a militant Jewish underground group that fought British mandatory rule in <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>. In 1940, he became a founder and leader of the `` Stern Gang'' which carried out a campaign of political assassinations and bombings of British installations. In 1948, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> ended the British mandate and established the state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Asked whether he was sorry he did n't complete his studies, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said: `` Not at all. I do n't regret anything I did.''
