<HEAD>Group Says Proposed New-Style Reactors Won't Help Global Warming
Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nuclear industry's proposed new-generation reactors, designed to operate more reliably and safely, will not be available soon enough to help the global warming problem, an anti-nuclear group said in a report Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Safe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said the nuclear industry was misleading the public by billing the advanced-design reactors as a partial solution to global atmospheric warming caused by emissions from fossil fuel plants. `` Nuclear power offers a ` fools gold' solution to global warming,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Denman </PERSON>, the group's director. <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Antypas </PERSON>, a researcher at the council, said it's too early to tell whether new reactor designs will prove better and more economic than the current generation. `` It will take at least 10 years to develop and build a single demonstration plant, and another two or more decades to bring many of those plants on line,'' <PERSON> Antypas </PERSON> said. The proposed new reactors would rely heavily on `` passive'' design features to guard against a melting of the reactor core. A gas-cooled reactor, for example, uses helium as a coolant instead of water and its core is encased in graphite. This gives its operators more time to respond to problems because the gas can not boil away and the graphite takes hours to reach a dangerous temperature. <PERSON> Antypas </PERSON> said that even if the advanced-design reactors prove more safe and reliable than the current light-water reactors, the industry still will not have solved the problem of long-term disposal of wastes generated by the plants. The group said more emphasis should be placed on improving energy efficiency in transportation, buildings, appliances and utilities instead of spending billions on new nuclear plants. Many in the nuclear industry believe that widespread adoption of the new reactor technologies is vital to restoring public confidence in the safety and efficiency of nuclear power.
