<HEAD>Bill Moves Forward in Jailed Mother Custody Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA WOMACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee on Tuesday passed legislation that would limit civil contempt of court jailings in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, a bill designed to help a mother who has been jailed 22 months in a child custody dispute. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, a prominent plastic surgeon, was jailed by <ORGANIZATION> D.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> after she refused to tell him where she had sent her six-year-old daughter <PERSON> Hilary </PERSON>. He has said repeatedly he will not lift his contempt citation until she gives the information. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> has been trying to prevent any visit between the child and <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Foretich </PERSON>, the girl's father. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> has accused <PERSON> Foretich </PERSON>, her former husband, of sexually abusing the child; he has repeatedly denied it. The legislation, designed to apply retroactively to <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s case, would limit civil contempt jailings in the district to 12 months, unless the judge in the case changes the charge to criminal contempt, a charge that would require a trial People could be held on criminal contempt charges during the trial, but not longer than 18 months. The bill also requires that a different judge hear the criminal contempt charges. `` We do not seek to place a limitation on the amount of time an individual can be sentenced to serve if convicted of criminal contempt,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Parris </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., a co-sponsor of the bill passed by the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` Our aim was to preserve the basic right of individuals to due process under the law.'' Nine of the members of the committee voted for the legislation, with only Rep. <PERSON> Mervyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Dymally </PERSON>, D-Calif., voting against it <PERSON> Parris </PERSON> said the legislation is expected to go before the full House next week. The panel's action came a day after <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> ruled again that the mother must remain behind bars until she discloses the whereabouts of her daughter or turns the child over to the city's foster care department. A District of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> panel had directed <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> to justify his December 1988 decision to keep <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> in jail. <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>'s latest ruling will now be reviewed by that three-judge panel. <PERSON> Foretich </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Mittleman </PERSON>, said Tuesday in a statement, `` Civil contempt does not transform into criminal contempt. ... A crime such as obstruction of justice is much more suited to Dr. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>'s offenses than is criminal contempt.''
