<SECOND>AM-Child Health,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Oppose Measures to Make Them Expand Eligibility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Physicians and children's advocates told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday that making more women eligible for Medicaid prenatal care would help reduce the nation's high rate of infant deaths. However, the states, which share the cost of the health insurance program for the poor with the federal government, opposed measures backed by the administration and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> requiring states to expand eligibility in their Medicaid programs. The administration is proposing to require states to admit to their Medicaid programs women and infants with incomes up to 130 percent of poverty. Sens. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-R.I. </LOCATION>, introduced a bill Monday to require coverage for women and children up to 185 percent of poverty. The need for prenatal care to reduce infant mortality `` has to be one of the nation's most pressing problems,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said at Tuesday's hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which he chairs. `` White American babies now die at a greater rate than babies born in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Minority babies born in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> today have a greater chance of dying before their first birthday than babies in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> infant mortality rate ranks 20th among industrialized nations, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. A third of all pregnant women are not receiving prenatal care, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said, and one in five children have no health insurance. `` The best way to ensure that a child will begin life as healthy as possible is to ensure the health of the mother during pregnancy through prenatal care,'' said <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of the Children's Defense Fund. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Obstetricians </ORGANIZATION> and Gynecologists said the evidence is overwhelming that prenatal care reduces low birthweight. This condition, he said, is associated with two-thirds of neonatal deaths and 20 percent of postnatal deaths. Yet, Medicaid falls far short of meeting the health-care needs of poor women and children, witnesses said. Current law gives states until July 1, 1990, to cover all pregnant women and infants with incomes below the poverty line. Forty-four states now provide coverage to pregnant women and infants with family income below the poverty line, and 15 states provide such coverage for women and infants with incomes up to 185 percent of poverty, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s measure would require coverage for pregnant women and children up to age 6 with incomes below 185 percent of poverty, or $ 22,385 for a family of four, by Jan. 1, 1991. It would add 300,000 women and 1.6 million children. The change would cost about $ 1 billion annually, a cost that would have to be matched by the states. The administration's proposal would add a total of 374,000 women and children to the program and would pay for the change by reducing state matching funds for administrative costs. The states, however, oppose `` any further mandated eligibility requirements in the Medicaid program,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheppach </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. In the last year and a half, states have had to absorb the costs of sweeping changes in nursing home care and expanded benefits for the elderly, he said. Yet, states voluntarily have been moving to expand their Medicaid programs to make more women, infants and children eligible for benefits and will continue to make improvements as their budgets allow, he said. `` Individual states are in the best position to decide how Medicaid funds should be spent to assist citizens who are in need,'' he said.
