<HEAD>U.S. Arms Negotiator: Soviets More Willing to Allow Verification</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> welcomes the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s increased willingness to allow verification of nuclear weapons reductions and plans to build on that in new initiatives, the chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiator said Tuesday Negotiator <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> declined to discuss <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposals in detail, but said `` we have noticed that the Soviets have taken a much more open and constructive approach on verification in recent years.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal came Monday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as the superpowers resumed Strategic Arms Reduction Talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> after a seven-month recess. The president said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> should begin testing verification procedures during negotiations on reducing long-range nuclear forces, rather than waiting until a pact is completed. Such steps could involve trial inspections at each other's missile sites and discussions about equipment needed for verification, which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said could be the most complex issue facing negotiators Tuesday's editions of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted an unidentified official in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as saying negotiators plan to suggest around-the-clock monitoring of some ballistic missile factories and on-site checks of missile warheads, to start before any new agreement. The proposal also was reported to include a ban on some missile flight tests. <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> said that another aim of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan is to build support for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ratification of a future arms treaty. Several superpower arms control treaties, including the 1979 SALT II pact on limiting long-range nuclear arsenals, remained unratified because the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> decided the verification provisions were lax. <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> said progress on verification would not become a condition in the START talks. `` We will continue to move on all fronts,'' he said. `` We are not proposing these measures as a take-it-or-leave-it package.'' The talks, aimed at reducing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet long-range bombers, missiles and nuclear submarines by 30 percent to 50 percent, are the latest round in negotiations that began four years ago. <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> said at the news conference that their aim is to `` speed resolution of outstanding issues and give added momentum'' toward completing a treaty. Under Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s philosophy of more openness, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has allowed Western experts to tour a Soviet chemical weapons site for the first time as part of efforts to negotiate a global ban. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet scientists also have exchanged visits to each other's nuclear testing sites to examine ways of monitoring two 1970s treaties limiting atomic blasts that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> never approved. <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> confirmed that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's review of arms policy did not result in a change in the Strategic Defense Initiative, which calls for space-based missile defenses, a divisive issue since arms talks began. He rejected Soviet attempts to link a START treaty to agreement on what <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> says would be crippling curbs on SDI. On Monday, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON>, head of the Soviet delegation to the talks, met with <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> for 80 minutes at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mission. <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON> spoke of `` a good start'' and held out the prospect of unspecified Soviet initiatives. The talks are to last six to seven weeks. In detailed negotiations starting Wednesday with a full meeting of both delegations, <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> will lead the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team and <PERSON> Lem </PERSON> <PERSON> Masterkov </PERSON> will continue as Soviet negotiator under <PERSON> Nazarkin </PERSON>. Disputes have developed over <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s demand for including sea-based cruise missiles in the treaty and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s call for a ban on mobile missiles. At earlier talks boths sides agreed to lower ceilings of 6,000 nuclear warheads and 1,600 delivery vehicles _ missiles and bombers _ for each side.
