<HEAD>Neighborhood Fights Crime-Linked Apartment Building</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Francisco Street residents are tired of living in fear because of rampant drug dealing and prostitution in their neighborhood. So they're fighting back _ in small claims court. Fifteen homeowners and renters have filed mental anguish claims for $ 2,000 each against the owner of the five-unit apartment building residents contend is the wellspring of neighborhood crime, illicit sex and drugs, all linked to sales of cheap, potent crack cocaine. Instead of soda cans and drifting newspapers, the neighborhood of modest Victorians and new condominiums has been littered with used syringes and condoms. `` I ca n't walk down the street anytime,'' said <PERSON> Elisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>, 18. `` People think I'm a prostitute.'' Her 15-year-old brother was robbed at gunpoint. One neighbor found a bloody syringe next to his child's swing. A second encountered a prostitute having sex on a picnic bench outside his back door at noon. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, who has lived in the area for four years, said the neighborhood was being ruined by drug dealing on the sidewalks and prostitution in the schoolyard, constant traffic and the sounds of fighting inside two apartments linked to narcotics sales. `` Our purpose is not to gouge anyone for lots of money, but to get the criminality removed,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Perocier </PERSON>, who has lived on <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> for 29 years, said her car has been broken into twice and items have been stolen from her garage. She said a man across the street was burglarized twice by thieves who ripped his deadbolt locks off with crowbars. `` He came back Sunday morning and even his underwear was gone, and he was wondering what he was going to wear to work,'' <PERSON> Perocier </PERSON> said. Residents say the drug and crime problems have grown worse in the past year and a half. The small claims filed in Berkeley-Albany Municipal Court blame the apartment building owner for negligence, creating a nuisance and endangering the neighborhood. Judge <PERSON> Jennie </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhine </PERSON> will receive final evidence in the case Wednesday and will rule later. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said the small claims idea stemmed from news about a successful lawsuit by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> homeowners against airport officials who promised to abate noise but failed to follow through. Police spokesman Capt. <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the two-story apartment building in the middle of the block is well-known to police, who have served search warrants and made arrests there. <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetzel </PERSON>, who lives across the street, said she contacted owner <PERSON> Percy </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> about the problems there several times since last October. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' attorney, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, contends <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> filed a notice on April 18 to evict the alleged trouble-makers. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> complained that <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>'s strict rent control law makes eviction difficult. About the troublesome tenants, <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> is n't `` accepting any responsibility for their criminal behavior.'' Repeated calls to <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> were not returned. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said the apartment tenants have been evicted or have agreed to move soon. `` All we know is that the problem is at last being solved,'' he said. `` I know Mr. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> now has promised to clean this situation up, but the time it has taken has ruined our lives,'' said the resident who found the bloody syringe. He did not want to be identified. The neighborhood, in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>'s flatlands about a mile west of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> campus, has long had crime problems because of a busy thoroughfare nearby. Residents acknowledge that getting new neighbors in the apartment building wo n't eliminate all of their problems, but it will help. `` We will not do away with the petty kind of burglary that you have everywhere in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, but the problems of prostitution and fear on the street definitely will go away,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. `` If it can stay clean a year, I believe it will be solved.''
