<FIRST>r w AM-GasDecontrol     06-20 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gas Decontrol,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compromise Reached on Natural Gas Decontrol Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators on Tuesday resolved a key difference in bills to remove all federal price controls on natural gas by Jan. 1, 1993. The compromise bill is expected to be signed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> within a few weeks. It is not expected to have a noticeable effect on retail prices for natural gas because most gas under controls already is selling below the official ceilings. The energy industry supports decontrol, while some consumer groups oppose it. Some other consumer groups, however, have taken what amounts to a neutral position. The only difference between the original <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bills was in treatment of natural gas from newly drilled wells. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version had no provision for early deregulation of gas from such wells, whereas the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> wanted to lift price controls on them retroactive to March 23, 1989. In a compromise, the negotiators agreed that gas from wells drilled after the date of enactment of the legislation would be deregulated on May 15, 1991. All other gas not already decontrolled would be freed from the federal ceilings upon the renegotiation of sales contracts, or Jan. 1, 1993, whichever comes first. About two-thirds of the nation's natural gas was deregulated by the 1978 Natural Gas Policy Act. Natural gas accounts for about one-quarter of the nation's energy use. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration strongly supports complete decontrol, contending that it will stimulate more exploration for a fuel source needed to limit dependence on foreign oil. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed its original bill in April, while the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill was passed earlier this month. The compromise bill must be voted on by both houses again before it is sent to the White House.
</TEXT>
