<FIRST>r a AM-GalloTrademark     06-20 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gallo Trademark,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Younger Brother Can't Use Name as Trademark on Cheese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>, owners of the world's largest winery, won the right Tuesday to keep the younger brother they raised from using his own name as a trademark for his own cheese. A federal judge concluded that use of the name <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> on retail cheese is misleading because many consumers assume the brand is connected with E & amp; J Gallo winery. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> sells about 10,000 tons of grapes a year from his vineyards to his brothers but has no other connection with their winery, based at <LOCATION> Modesto </LOCATION>, 90 miles southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` There is substantial evidence of actual confusion,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> wrote, citing retailers who asked if the cheese and wine were connected. However, the judge's permanent injunction permits <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> to use his name as a signature or in block letters below the words designating the variety of cheese if the label also includes a prominent trademark above that does not include the word <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said he expects to win on appeal. He criticized <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> for appearing to use arguments by winery attorneys verbatim in his brief and failing to submit a decision separate from the findings and injunction. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said the findings failed to deal adequately with the question of whether `` a person is entitled to use his own full name on his own product.'' However, <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON>'s findings addressed the dilemma of using a common name that also is a well-known brand. `` If every person named <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> were entitled to use <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> as a consumer trademark, <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> might be adopted as a trademark on any imaginable product,'' <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> wrote. `` Such proliferation of uses would destroy the unique nature of the Gallo brand, its distinctiveness and its commercial value.'' A month-long trial last fall offered rare glimpses of the family-owned winery's development from a provider of bulk wines without a brand during the Depression to fame and fortune for its cheap wines _ first Thunderbird in the 1950s, later the Gallo brand itself. Gallo Winery's sales now total $ 1 billion a year. A Gallo attorney said during an opening statement that in 1933 _ six weeks after their father killed ther mother, then committed suicide _ <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> began making wine with knowledge gained from a book they got at the public library. <PERSON> Julio </PERSON>, now 79, has handled the winemaking ever since while <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON>, 80, became a widely recognized marketing expert. Even though they raised younger brother <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, now 67, after the deaths of their parents, the winery <PERSON> Gallos </PERSON> sued him after he began using his name on cheese in the mid 1980s. Winery attorney <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Wanger </PERSON> said Tuesday that <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> had to protect their trademark and a licensing agreement that let <ORGANIZATION> Gallo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Salami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> use the <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> name on cheese under an agreement by which winery inspectors checked that brand's quality. <ORGANIZATION> Gallo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Salami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has no other connection to the three <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> brothers. <PERSON> Wanger </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> were reluctant to sue their brother but were rebuffed when they offered to license him to use the <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> trademark if the winery were allowed reasonable quality control over his cheese. <PERSON> Coyle </PERSON> also commented on the issue of quality control, saying the winery and <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> <PERSON> Salami </PERSON> `` have reasonable grounds to be concerned that sale of cheeses by defendants under the <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo </PERSON> brand creates an undue and unnecessary risk of a serious health problem resulting from the sale of <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallo-brand </PERSON> cheese that may injure the Gallo brand.''
