<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> appointed lay businessman and bankers to manage its scandal-tainted bank Tuesday, ending the 20-year presidency of American Archbishop <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcinkus </PERSON>. `` In principle, laymen should be more competent in financial affairs than clerics,'' said <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON>. He identified an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessman and bankers from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> who were named to the bank's supervisory board They will appoint a lay director and deputy director. Police said another banker wanted in connection with <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s worst postwar banking scandal flew to <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> on Tuesday and surrendered to authorities Banker <PERSON> Umberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortolani </PERSON> faces charges of fraudulent bankruptcy following the 1982 collapse of <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ambrosiano </ORGANIZATION>. Judges investigating the collapse of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s largest private bank have charged <PERSON> Ortolani </PERSON> with stealing $ 230 million from the Milan-based bank. <PERSON> Marcinkus </PERSON> and two lay <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> bank officials were charged with being accessories to the bankruptcy, and warrants were issued for their arrests in 1987. But the arrests never were carried out. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled a Vatican-Italian treaty prevents Italian authorities from interfering in affairs of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, the city that is an independent state. <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials denied wrongdoing in the collapse of <ORGANIZATIO