<HEAD>Pentagon Says No Harm Done by Substitutions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Aerodyne Indictments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Armed Services have yet to detect any safety problems because of the alleged illegal substitution of scrap metal for designated alloys in engines for 5,000 military aircraft, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. According to a fraud indictment Monday in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, of three former executives of <ORGANIZATION> Aerodyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the company used scrap in making turbine blades of the type used in 22,000 jet aircraft, helicopters and tanks. `` Now, it's estimated that 5,000 aircraft have been equipped with these parts since 1982,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. `` Two million hours have been accrued on the aircraft without any known related incidents. `` There has been no noticeable degradation in performance using that 50-percent mixture.'' The blades were used in T-53 engine that's used on the Huey, Cobra and <LOCATION> Mohawk </LOCATION> helicopters for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> suspended the contractor last Aug. 16 `` because of the evidence of <ORGANIZATION> Aerodyne </ORGANIZATION>'s use of nonspecified alloys in making parts'' said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. The grand jury indicted three former <ORGANIZATION> Aerodyne </ORGANIZATION> executives, <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> Sr. and <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Carman </PERSON> <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said the alleged fraud was discovered by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s inspector general, who notified the military services and the <ORGANIZAT