<HEAD>Senate Committee Approves Measure to Deal with Oil Spills</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Oil Spill Plan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee approved a bill Tuesday designed to deal with oil spills and try to prevent them through such steps as random alcohol testing of crews and improved radar systems for tracking tankers. The Oil Tanker Navigation Safety Act of 1989 deals directly with <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, where <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> continues cleaning up a massive spill, and would also affect tanker operations elsewhere. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Transporation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> announced a comprehensive inspection of the 800-mile <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> pipeline. He indicated that the March 24 rupture of the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> oil tanker prompted the inspection, originally set for 1991. `` The Exxon Valdez oil spill has taught us a valuable lesson: the need to avoid complacency when it comes to protecting our environment,'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said. He said the inspection will review operating pressures, repair procedures, protective coating requirements, routine inspection schedules and the electric current used to retard corrosion, along with oil spill contingency plans for the pipeline. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> also sent <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> a proposed bill to give the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> broader authority over mariners, including revocation of their certification if they have a record of drunken driving. That and several other provisions already were in the bill approved without opposition by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The bill, backed by Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, would open highway driving records of merchant mariners to the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, provide for random and other alcohol testing of people in safety-senstive jobs on tankers and improve radar systems to aid the tracking of ships through potentially hazardous areas. It also requires the secretary of transportation to examine several other safety steps and sets guidelines for oil spill contingency plans, including requiring some oil spill cleanup equipment to be prepositioned at strategic locations and other equipment to be carried aboard tankers. The legislation, consolidating six proposed bills arising from three <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearings on the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> spill, was sent to the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as the oil industry unveiled its own plan for responding to major spills. The industry announced it would spend $ 250 million to set up a network of response teams capable of handling an accident as large as the March 24 disaster involving the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill would require at least three persons to be on the bridge of a tanker in certain waters, including the sound. The Exxon Valdez's captain had gone below deck and turned the helm over to his third mate, who was not licensed to navigate the sound. The captain, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>, faces several charges in connection with the incident. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measure would allow suspension of a merchant marine's license, following a hearing, for being drunk on the job or if there is a record of a highway driver's license being suspended or revoked within the previous five years for alcohol or drug use The legislation instructs the transportation secretary to examine whether newly constructed tankers should be built with double hulls or double bottoms and also to conduct a study of whether the size of tankers being built is a factor in oil spills. The Exxon Valdez carried over 50 million gallons. Sen. <PERSON> Slade </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorton </PERSON>, R-Wash., said he would propose on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor an amendment that would impose financial punishment on companies responsible for oil spills, including a possible giving up of all profits for one year if in a case of `` gross or willful negligence. The money would go into an environmental fund.
