<HEAD>Quayle Promises to Shore Up U.S. Trade Interests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs `I share ...' with 1 graf to CORRECT that
National Foreign Trade Council is separate from National Association of
Manufacturers and ADD third group. Picks up 4th graf pvs `The Council ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s committee to enhance <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade competitiveness began work Tuesday as Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> promised to shore up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests against the consolidation of European markets. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Competitiveness </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s plan to restructure its economies into a single European market by 1992 has caused concern among <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses. `` I share some of those concerns, but fundamentally EC-92 is both a challenge and an opportunity for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> and the Coalition For Employment Through Exports. The Council on Competitiveness, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, will review federal laws to ensure they do n't unfairly restrict <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies against European competitors. The vice president said the council also would ensure <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> access to and fair competition in the single European market, and would re-evaluate policies on deregulation of financial institutions and anti-trust restrictions. American companies complain that antitrust measures prevent them from competing fairly because European countries are not restrained by the same standards. Many of the antitrust policies are `` anachronistic in this age of global competition,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, adding that merger law reform is needed. `` We need to consider reducing present incentives for price antitrust litigation,'' he said. The vice president said the area of biotechnology, in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been a leader, will be reviewed. `` The key to our success in marketing new biotechnology products has been a sensible regulatory regime that applies basic competitiveness principles,'' he said, but cautioned against unnecessary regulatory burdens on product development. `` We need to consider ways to improve incentives for private sector investment,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, citing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal to reduce the capital gains tax, make permanent tax credit payments for research and development and ease the patent applications process. The Council on Competitiveness, whose members include cabinet members involved with trade issues, was set up by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to continue the work of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s task force. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s task force dealt with eliminating excessive government regulation.
