<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Procurement     06-20 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Procurement,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Pay for Development Stage of Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, in a policy shift from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> era, has decided that the government will pay the full cost of readying new weapons for production, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said Tuesday. For the past eight years, government and defense contractors have split the development cost of most weapons systems. That policy will change, the new No. 2 <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official, Deputy <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>, revealed in a published interview. <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>'s proposal was embodied in a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> management review that <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> approved and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday, acording to other <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials. The policy change does not require congressional review. `` We're just going to implement it,'' said <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>. The old system does not encourage defense contractors to develop the most efficient weapons and means of producing them, <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON> said. `` It encourages them to skimp,'' he said in an interview with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. Pentagon officials distributed the text on Tuesday. `` The consequence is, lo and behold, we end up in production with something that's difficult to build. We did n't put the time and effort into it,'' said <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>, a former executive at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. He did not offer any specific examples, but the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> has had trouble in recent years in the performance of several costly weapons. The development contract, said <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>, `` is when you should put your effort into designing it for simplicity and producibility, of designing it for reliability and performance and quality. And it is not the time you skimp. That is the whole purpose.'' The shift, which is likely to be hailed by the defense industry, will not affect existing contracts on major weapons systems, such as the B-2 `` stealth'' bomber or a new class of attack submarines. But <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said in a statement that future contracts for full-scale development of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s new Advanced Technology Fighter `` may reflect the change in contract policy.'' In outlining the new policy, <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON> distinguished between research that contractors pursue on various weapons-related technologies and the money they spend developing actual weapons for the government. `` I think the government should pay the bill for the development phase,'' he said. `` By the development, I mean the early-on demonstration, validation phase, and for the full-scale development.'' `` Now, I do n't want to hold out any bonanza to any industry that thinks, ` Well, we'll get all the money we want. Quite the contrary,'' he said.
