<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> confirmed Tuesday it will make a closer study of environmental risks posed by a prototype plutonium refinery, a move that a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel chairman says will delay start of plant construction at least two years. The department has called the plant a key to modernization of the nation's nuclear weapons production complex. It would use a new laser technology to convert existing military stockpiles of fuel-grade plutonium to weapon-grade material. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Spratt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, chairman of a special <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> panel, said <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> had made the decision in response to an environmental group's threat last April to sue to force such a study. <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Callicott </PERSON>, a department spokesman, said <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> had notified selected members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of his decison on Monday and Tuesday, although no general announcement was made. The move was made, <PERSON> Callicott </PERSON> said, because of `` our own wish to put any public doubt to rest ... as to the environmental safeguards for the project.'' He declined to say how long the environmental study would delay the refinery project. <PERSON> Spratt </PERSON> said <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> had committed the department to conducting a formal Environmental Impact Statement on the prototype, which is being built at the department's <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The Livermore project is a prototype for a permanent plutonium refinery, called the Special Isotope Separation plant, that the department wants to build at the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, near <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>. An environmental study of the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> site already has been completed. <PERSON> Spratt </PERSON>'s panel, which is reviewing <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plans for modernizing the nuclear weapons complex and cleaning up its hazardous wastes, last week voted to recommend withholding funds for beginning construction at <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> in 1990. In a statement announcing <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>' decision, <PERSON> Spratt </PERSON> said he was pleased by the move. `` It signifies to the people of <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION> and vicinity that their concerns for health and safety are shared by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, and more broadly, it is a tangible sign of what Secretary <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> calls a ` change of culture' at <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. The Natural Resources Defense Council, which notified the department last April that it would sue if an environmental assessment were not performed, said it was pleased by the decision. `` We scored a victory,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Reicher </PERSON> of the council. `` It's a combination of the strong position we believe we have, plus congressional pressure. <PERSON> Spratt </PERSON> said it would take at least 12 months to finish the environmental study, and that the start of construction at <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> is likely to be delayed at least two years.
