<HEAD>Report Says Star Wars Research Less Costly Than Bush Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can conduct Star Wars research and development far more cheaply than the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is proposing, acording to a congressional report released Tuesday. The three types of budget options described in the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report would cost $ 11.3 billion to $ 18.4 billion from 1990 to 1994, rather than the $ 31.1 billion proposed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for the same period. `` If we spend billions on strategic defense that does not really defend us _ and siphon these billions from the budgets of fighter planes, ships, tanks and personnel _ we may not make the country more secure,'' said Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Spratt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> who requested the report. `` For this reason, the <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> report bears careful study.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cut spending on the Strategic Defense Initiative to $ 4.6 billion for fiscal 1990, down from the $ 5.9 billion proposed by former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> has also said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will shift the focus of Star Wars from deployment sometime in the 1990s to research on a more advanced system known as `` Brilliant Pebbles,'' consisting of thousands of orbiting satellites. Under the report's first option, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be protected against a Soviet breakthrough in technology or the Kremlin's deployment of a strategic defense system. Total spending would range from $ 11.3 billion to $ 14.5 billion and the option would be in compliance with the Anti-ballistic Missile Treaty, the report said. The second option, estimated at a cost of about $ 17 billion, would enable the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to defend parts of the country against a limited nuclear attack caused by an accident. That option may comply with the ABM Treaty, the report said. The third option, costing about $ 18.4 billion, would provide a larger strategic defense system that would protect land-based missiles housed in silos such as the MX and Midgetman. The report estimates did not include the cost of procuring the system.
