<HEAD>Pollution News Shocking But Not Surprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOOELE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents of this arid county in western <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, home to military installations, industrial plants and waste disposal facilities, are no strangers to pollution hazards. And now, state officials have been told that <ORGANIZATION> AMAX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magnesium </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which extracts metal from evaporation ponds on the western shore of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, is the nation's single greatest source of toxic air pollutants, specifically chlorine, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` Certainly we're not proud of the designation,'' <ORGANIZATION> AMAX </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` But the fact is, we've been cognizant of the emissions and have done environmental studies that show absolutely no discernable effects.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said the plant, about 65 miles from <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and 40 miles from the nearest community, employs about 600 workers who extract magnesium chloride salt from the briny water and process magnesium and liquid chloride for a variety of industrial uses. Even now, the company is installing devices to reduce the emission of chlorine gas from the stacks by 50 percent at year's end and a total of 75 percent by 1991, state environmental health officials say. What concerns some officials more than <ORGANIZATION> AMAX </ORGANIZATION>'s emissions is that <LOCATION> Tooele </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, with its immense deserts and desolate mountains, has become a favorite destination for low-level hazardous wastes from producers in and out of the state. Radioactive tailings from an old uranium mill in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> are buried there. Hazardous waste disposal sites are in operation or on the drawing boards, one waste incinerator is under construction and another has been proposed. At Dugway Proving Ground, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> has conducted germ warfare defense testing for decades, and <ORGANIZATION> Tooele </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> stores much of the nation's arsenal of obsolete chemical weapons. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> uses hundreds of square miles of the county for bombing runs and jet fighter training. `` People drive out there, and they think of all this wasted land,'' said state Rep. <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a 10-term Democrat. `` But we have mountains, streams and deserts. It is n't just nothing. I've been saying for years that I hope we do n't turn into the dumping ground of the world. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> shares her concerns. He praised the strict criteria county officials have established for siting, mitigation and emergency response capabilities when approving new hazardous waste and other developments with a potential for pollution. `` But along with expertise in knowing how to handle, manage and work with a hazardous management zone, comes a feeling of growing confidence,'' he said. `` Just like with TAD, there's an attitude of, ` We can live with these things.' Is Tooele going to be the hazardous-waste frontier?'' However, <LOCATION> Tooele </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON> says the potential perils of hazardous waste and pollution or accidents at Dugway or <ORGANIZATION> Tooele </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> must be weighed with the economic benefits to its 30,000 residents. Besides, he said, all are strictly regulated by a variety of local, state and federal agencies. `` I'm not trying to downplay the health factors,'' he said. `` But we are trying to balance the two _ health factors and economics.''
