<HEAD>House Panel OKs Tax Penalty Revisions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation Tuesday revising and simplifying most of the nearly 150 federal tax penalties. The measure generally would require the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to be less harsh on a taxpayer who tries to comply with the law but fails than on one who makes no effort to comply. It also aims to reduce chances that a taxpayer will be hit with two or more civil penalties for the same shortcoming. The committee, meeting behind closed doors, added the provision to a package that eventually is expected to include spending cuts and revenue increases required to reduce the budget deficit. Rep. <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said that his oversight subcommittee heard testimony that `` the current penalty structure is a confusing morass of complex, overlapping penalties that are often unduly harsh or just plain irrational.'' The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>, 35 years ago, had only 13 penalties to enforce. The increase, authorities say, is due in part to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' use of penalties to raise revenue. The rewriting is based on the notion that penalties should be used only to encourage compliance, not to raise money. In 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> assessed 26 million penalties totaling nearly $ 6 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> supports overhauling the penalty structure. Present law imposes a 5 percent penalty for underpayment of tax; the bill would raise that generally to 20 percent. Most of the changes involve penalties on banks and others that fail to file reports on interest and dividends, and on employers who miss the deadline for turning over withheld taxes to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>. In most cases, the revised penalties would be graduated so that the longer the delay in paying or filing, the higher the penalty.
