egulations that faced staunch GOP opposition. Tacked on to the Dodd-Hatch bill were two proposals approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a new, up-to - $ 500, tax credit to help families pay for health insurance for children and a provision making refundable the existing dependent care tax credit The Republican alternative <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> planned to offer _ with the blessing of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> _ would rely almost entirely on tax credits to help parents pay for child care. It too would make the dependent-care credit refundable and create a new child care tax credit for low-income families with children up to 4 years old. The <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> proposal also would create a $ 400 million block grant program to help states expand child care opportunities.
