<HEAD>Attention Turns to Presidency After Polish Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Official results Tuesday confirmed that Solidarity clinched 260 of the 261 seats it was allowed to contest in the new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, guaranteeing the union a veto over <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> legislation. But two days after Sunday's voting, politicians from both sides already were turning attention to the election of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s first president in 37 years. Results issued by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> showed Solidarity holding 99 of 100 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first democratically elected parliament chamber The independent union also gained 161 seats in the lower house, the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION>, compared to 299 seats held by the Communist-led coalition. That gave the Communist coalition 65 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> seats and Solidarity 35 percent, the ratio permitted under a pre-election bargain. But the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had only 173 of the coalition seats, making it technically a minority. Minor pro-government <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> groups made up the remainder of coalition places. And among the Communist coalition's seats, at least 46 were progressives endorsed by Solidarity. Several prominent hard-line Communists were defeated. `` There is hope that in the new <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> we will find partners who understand our causes and who, like us, favor the process of reform,'' Solidarity spokesman <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said Tuesday. The two sides in the Assembly will be roughly balanced so that `` either there will be cooperation between the coalition and the opposition or we will face a chain of conflicts that will block the legislative process,'' said government spokesman <PERSON> Zbyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Rykowski </PERSON>. In a next step, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> convenes within 30 days to choose a president. The Communist coalition enters the meeting with about 40 more votes than the opposition, although there could be defections. Choosing the president is the last stage of the political bargain struck April 5 between the Solidarity-led opposition and Communist authorities after two months of talks. The accord led to the restoration of Solidarity's legal status after a seven-year ban and the holding of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s freest parliamentary elections since World War II. The new president will sign legislation and be commander-in-chief of the armed forces. The president will serve one six-year term. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> had five presidents between 1918, when the modern Polish state was established, and 1952, when the office was abolished by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The president in turn will nominate the next prime minister, who will form a government. Although <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, who now leads the country, is assumed to be the party's candidate, his spokesman last week said he still has not decided to run.
