<FIRST>r i AM-Africa-Pollution     06-20 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Africa-Pollution,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Discover Air Pollution Over Much of Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists have discovered air pollution over much of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and it is chemically similar to the smog that plagues southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, a research leader said Tuesday. <PERSON> Meinrat </PERSON> <PERSON> Andreae </PERSON>, a chemist with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Max </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said the deliberate burning of huge savanna areas produces acid rain and ozone pollution that settles over <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s rain forests `` These levels we've seen over the rain forests are dramatically higher than anything anybody has seen over rain forests before,'' <PERSON> Andreae </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Andreae </PERSON> headed the West German group in a 20-member project that included scientists from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION>. He said his team spent two weeks in the field in the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION> in February and March of 1988. <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s air pollution is `` a combination of atmospheric pollutants which is very similar to the sort of smog-type chemistry that you get in southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Andreae </PERSON> said. `` When the smoke plume spends some time in the atmosphere and has the sunshine burning on top of it, you start photochemical reactions just like in any old smog situation in southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.'' He said the acidity and ozone levels are similar to those in some industrialized areas of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and he noted such levels damage plants, lakes and forests. `` There is no reason ... to assume that the equatorial forests should be more resistant to these sort of pollutant impacts than those in temperate regions,'' <PERSON> Andreae </PERSON> added. He said that while the team's field work was done in the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION> that country is not a source of the pollutants. The area affected by the pollution runs from the `` southern edge of the <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> down to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` It's a phenomenon that essentially covers all of tropical <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` Any country where there are savannas there will be large-scale burning, typically once a year, sometimes every two years. All the savannas are burned periodically for agricultural purposes. The farmers like to burn the shrub and grass in order to remove the old dry grass and get the fresh grass to sprout. `` The amount of burning is increasing rather dramatically, and also the area covered by burns,'' he said. `` There are more people _ the population of all those regions is growing dramatically.'' <PERSON> Andreae </PERSON> is a director of the <ORGANIZATION> Max </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemistry </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Mainz </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
