<HEAD>Northern Civil Rights Workers Commemorate 1964 Murders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with caravan arriving for night
in Meridian. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `An FBI...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MERIDIAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of northern civil rights workers arrived in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> on Tuesday to relive _ for one day _ the long, hot summer of 1964. The riders, predominantly blacks, traveled 30 hours from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. They came to take part in memorial services commemorating the murders of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON> on June 21, 1964. `` This state has a dark history and I wanted to see what <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> is like,'' said <PERSON> Viola </PERSON> <PERSON> Sulton </PERSON>, 76, of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. An <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation revealed <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON> were killed by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> and their bodies were buried in an earthen dam near <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, 40 miles north of here The murders occurred while the three volunteers were trying to keep alive a voter registration drive in neighboring <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> is located. The crime was one of the most sensational events during the civil rights movement of the 1960s. The killings, and subsequent coverup by <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> officials, ignited indignation around the country and marked a dramatic and tragic beginning to the so-called `` Mississippi Freedom Summer Project,'' which brought young people from the North pouring into <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. Tuesday's caravan was modeled after those earlier caravans. It was scheduled to spend the night in <LOCATION> Meridian </LOCATION> and go on to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> Wednesday for a day of ceremonies marking the 25th anniversary of the murders. <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> McClain </PERSON> said his town was ready for the visitors, which were to include relatives of the victims and the governors of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. `` I have to admit our people have mixed emotions about this event,'' <PERSON> McClain </PERSON> said Tuesday while attending a <ORGANIZATION> Meridian </ORGANIZATION> luncheon for relatives of <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, a native son of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and former resident of <LOCATION> Meridian </LOCATION>. <PERSON> McClain </PERSON> added he did n't expect any trouble on Wednesday but acknowledged that not everybody in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, a farming community of 7,000 residents, is happy about the memorial service. However, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Molpus </PERSON> said state officials hope to use the event to show the world that many positive changes have taken place in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> since the bloody summer of 1964. `` We intend to send a message to the nation that the only thing burning in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> today is a desire for a better life for all our people,'' <PERSON> Molpus </PERSON> said, in an oblique reference to `` Mississippi Burning,'' a recent, controversial movie about the murders. <PERSON> McClain </PERSON>, meanwhile, said he had doubts about <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s statement last weekend that he might reopen a state investigation of the 1964 murders. `` It could be a pretty rocky thing for our community,'' <PERSON> McClain </PERSON> said. `` We've come 25 years and made a lot of progress and a reopening of the murder investigation could set us back to ground zero.'' <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, brother of the slain <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, differed with <PERSON> McClain </PERSON>. `` I think it would be good to reopen the case,'' he said Tuesday. `` An investigation might help bring out some of the terrible things that happened in <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> back then, such as the beatings at the Mt. Zion Methodist Church shortly before the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> burned the church.'' Wednesday's commemoration ceremonies are set to begin at the small, predominantly black church on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. The church was rebuilt the year after it was burned by the klan. On the day they were killed, <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> _ white volunteers from the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> area _ went with <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> to visit church members and keep alive a fledgling voters registration drive in that county. They were jailed on a traffic charge and later turned over to a <ORGANIZATION> KKK </ORGANIZATION> mob which killed them and buried the bodies. The state never did bring murder charges in the case but 19 Mississipians, most from the Meridian and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> areas, were prosecuted under federal laws for violating the civil rights of the three victims. Seven men eventually were convicted and an eighth pleaded guilty. Their prison sentences ranged from three to 10 years prison but the most any ever served was six years. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representitives </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday declared Wednesday to be `` Chaney, <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> and Schwerner Day'' in honor of the three victims. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed an identical resolution on June 9.
