<HEAD>Subcommittee Chairmen Say Old-Growth Logging A National Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three House subcommittee chairmen warned Tuesday the fight over logging in the ancient forests of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> was more than just a regional conflict and they would keep a close watch to ensure national interests were protected. The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Yates </PERSON>, D-Ill., offered an amendment to the interior appropriations bill which would have forced the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to provide for cutting methods in all timber sales that would result in `` minimal fragmentation'' of remaining old-growth stands The two Northwest members of the subcommittee, Rep. <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON>, D-Wash., and Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON>, D-Ore., were caught off guard by <PERSON> Yates </PERSON>' amendment and quickly <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> agreed to withdraw the amendment, but said he might offer it again when the full committee considers the bill. `` My intent was to protect old growth to the greatest extent possible,'' <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> said. `` This is a national issue.'' Meanwhile, the chairmen of two other subcommittees said during a joint hearing that they too were concerned. `` Although these forests are found primarily in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, all Americans have a stake in them,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Vento </PERSON>, chairman of the national parks and public lands subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Volkmer </PERSON>, D-Mo., chairman of the fore