<HEAD>More Than 50,000 Ethnic Turks Leave Bulgaria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 50,000 ethnic Turks have poured across the border from <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> since May to escape government persecution, officials said Tuesday. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Mesut </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilmaz </PERSON> on Monday took 53 ambassadors to the frontier and called for world condemnation of the <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s `` primitive'' policies He urged the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to take up the issue. <PERSON> Yilmaz </PERSON> also said <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> expected a clearer stand from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> bloc countries, particularly the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, on the problem. In 1983, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> implemented a forced assimilation campaign, under which ethnic Turks were to change their Moslem names to Christian Slavic ones. The campaign also barred the public use of the Turkish language and the practice of Islamic rites. In May, ethnic Turks demonstrated against the campaign and police attacked them with dogs and clubs, killing about 40 people. On May 26, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> began mass deportations of ethnic Turks they said were leading the protests. Premier <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> on Tuesday reiterated his call to <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> to open negotiations on the immigration of ethnic Turks. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> says the Moslem minority numbers 780,000, while Turkish officials put it at 2.5 million in the total population of 9 million. <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> has proposed talks on an immigration agreement that would allow ethnic Turks to dispose of their property and bring out liquid assets. Deportees have said they were not allowed to take with them more than a suitcase. Through defections and immigration agreements, 380,00 ethnic Turks have come to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> since 1925.
