<HEAD>Arkansas Congressman Won't Run Again; Blames Coelho for Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former House Majority Whip <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> was `` throwing money away like crazy to get elected whip,'' leaving the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> heavily in debt, its chairman said Tuesday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> newspaper that he inherited a $ 1.4 million debt from <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, a former representative from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> said he then had to borrow more money to fulfill promises <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> had made, raising the debt to $ 1.8 million. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> said that was part of the reason he was not going to seek a third term as chairman of the committee, which he said <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> had turned into a political machine to which countless House Democrats were indebted. `` Everybody thought <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> was the greatest thing since sliced bread,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>, also a Democrat. `` Yet I took over a committee burdened with a huge debt purely and simply because <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> was throwing money away like crazy to get elected whip. He would give members anything they wanted in return for a commitment.'' Telephone calls made by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> to <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> office were not answered Tuesday. <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> became <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority whip in 1987. He resigned recently in the face of a likely ethics inquiry into his financial dealings. The committee's debt is nearly three times its reported 1987 debt. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>, named committee chairman in December 1986 and re-elected without opposition in January to a second, two-year term, said he worked until September 1987 to reduce the inherited debt. `` I was n't able to start raising funds for my tenure as chairman for nine months,'' he said. `` Still, I attempted to put things in as positive a light as possible.'' The debt shot back up last fall, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> said, because he had to borrow more money late in the election cycle to fulfill promises to candidates. The committee generates money for distribution to party members seeking House seats. `` This committee certainly is not in worse shape than it was when I took over,'' he said. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> also said knowledge of the debt did not hurt him in the race to succeed <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority whip. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> finished third with 30 of 261 votes cast. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> said he has not talked about the debt in the past because there was `` nothing to be gained at the time by pointing fingers.'' But now that <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> is gone, `` there is no reason to keep it a big, dark secret.''
