<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     06-20 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The Loman Family Picnic,' A Play by Donald Margulies, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mix <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> with <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and a bit of <PERSON> Jule </PERSON> <PERSON> Styne </PERSON>, and you'll get `` The Loman Family Picnic'' by <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Margulies </PERSON>. This odd yet imaginative domestic free-for-all, which opened Tuesday at <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>'s Stage II, keeps the audience off-balance for most of the evening as the story switches from low comedy to high drama to hard-sell musical comedy. The changes of gear could be unsettling, but the playwright and director <PERSON> Barnet </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellman </PERSON> manage to keep everything spinning for much of the time. `` On the day I was married, the world showed every sign of coming to an end,'' says the play's 38-year-old heroine, <PERSON> Doris </PERSON>. It did n't _ and neither did her marriage to a drab lighting fixture salesman named <PERSON> Herbie </PERSON>. Instead, their lives in a middle-class <LOCATION> Coney </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> apartment building just went on and on. The years were highlighted by the arrival of two sons, <PERSON> Stewie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. The play, set in 1965, turns on <PERSON> Stewie </PERSON>'s bar mitzvah, and all the problems and pressures it produces. Like <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> Loman </PERSON> in <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s `` Death of a Salesman,'' <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> dreams of a better life and actually believes she has found one with <PERSON> Herbie </PERSON>. And like <PERSON> Willy </PERSON>, who idolized his successful and adventurous Uncle <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON>, <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> adores her late and lamented <PERSON> Aunt </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsha </PERSON> who died at age 23. The ghost of Uncle <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> hovers over <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s classic <PERSON> Aunt </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsha </PERSON>, a tough-talking, sexy young woman, does the same in `` The Loman Family Picnic.'' <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> and <PERSON> Herbie </PERSON> do n't really talk. <PERSON> Margulies </PERSON>' dialogue between husband and wife is a model of non-communication. They do n't say what's on their minds until it is too late. The wife focuses her attention on her sons _ the older <PERSON> Stewie </PERSON>, played with authentic obnoxiousness by <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> <PERSON> Trichter </PERSON>, and the more artistic and sensitive <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, portrayed with charm and grace by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Miceli </PERSON>. Instead of a writing a book report on `` Death of a Salesman,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> creates a mini-musical comedy. He calls it `` Willy!'' and it bursts upon the stage late in Act 2 after the family has had a major blow-up over the bar mitzvah. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s music for `` Willy!'' is by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Shire </PERSON>, composer of `` Baby'' and `` Starting Here, Starting Now.'' It has the brassy, uptempo sound of a Styne show, a style totally at odds with the humdrum happenings on stage. But that's the point of <PERSON> Margulies </PERSON>' family tale The playwright even adds several alternate endings to the play, imagining what the characters would like to happen and what really does. It's funny and a bit sad at the same time. <PERSON> Marcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON> gives a marvelously funny and touching performance as the mother. <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> refuses to give up or grow old. Dressed as the Bride of Frankenstein, she goes trick or treating with her sons on Halloween and cuts up her wedding dress for a costume. She keeps repeating, `` I love my life, I love my life, I love my life,'' and you believe her. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Block </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s most underrated character actors, excels as <PERSON> Herbie </PERSON>. He's a superb physical comedian and a master of timing. Watch him as he forces himself to eat the diet tuna plate <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> prepares each evening for him. <PERSON> Kellman </PERSON> has a difficult job separating the fantasies from real life but with the help of the imaginative lighting by <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kletter </PERSON> and his hardy troupe of actors, he does just that. Out the living room window looms a non-descript apartment building, much like the high-rises that hem in the <PERSON> Loman </PERSON> home in <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s play. Designer G.W. <PERSON> Mercier </PERSON> has an eye for detail, down to the family's hideous <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> furniture and shag carpeting that covers the tiny stage. `` The Loman Family Picnic'' is an unusual play. It echoes <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Styne </PERSON>, but it can stand on its own as an original piece of theater.
</TEXT>
