<HEAD>Wildfires Threaten Southern California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wildfire apparently started by target shooters raged through <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> brush Tuesday, roaring to within 1,000 feet of a desert neighborhood where 85 homes were abandoned by fleeing residents. The 600-acre blaze, one of several brush fires in <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> counties, was driven by 45 mph winds and fed on dense, brittle vegetation as temperatures soared into the 100s. Firefighters were managing to keep the flames away from the <LOCATION> Yucca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> homes late Tuesday. No injuries were reported and no houses were damaged, said <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> McClellan </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION>. `` The fire was running in really close. The wind is causing the firefighters problems. The evacuation was voluntary but about 85 homes were evacuated,'' <PERSON> McClellan </PERSON> said. The fire doubled in size in just a half hour and apparently was started by people target shooting at utility poles, <PERSON> McClellan </PERSON> said. Other than the neighborhood threatened, the area 110 miles east of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> was a sparsely populated stretch of desert skirting the <ORGANIZATION> Joshua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monument </ORGANIZATION>. The monument was not threatened, said <PERSON> McClellan </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Ventura </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, a 300-acre brush fire was being fought by more than 200 firefighters, and a 115-acre blaze in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> kept about 60 firefighters busy. No damages or injuries were reported in those fires.
