<HEAD>Four Arrested in Baby-Selling Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four people, including a father-and-daughter attorney team, were arrested Tuesday for allegedly bilking desperate couples of $ 500,000 in a baby-selling scheme that spanned 21 states and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The group `` preyed upon the emotions of these couples'' and `` in effect, engaged in a black market baby-selling operation,'' said state Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>. The four were named in 144-count indictment alleging they arranged illegal adoptions for about 100 couples from around the country. Fifty couples wound up with the infants between 1983 and 1988, <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said. An investigation disclosed that the defendants enticed prospective parents into paying extra fees and supposed expenses of the birth mothers, <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said. Some prospective parents paid up to $ 16,000 and did not receive a child or receive their money back, <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said. The couples were told the birth mothers had miscarried or changed their minds. The babies were found primarily through advertisements placed in a supermarket checkout counter tabloid, and the couples who wanted babies were found through word of mouth, officials said. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said neither the mothers who gave up their children nor the parents who adopted the infants face any charges. The four were charged with grand larceny, conspiracy, fraud, perjury, filing false documents and making false statements. The charges stem from the illegal operation of Child Haven of <LOCATION> Northeastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, a private adoption agency. They pleaded innocent before <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkman </PERSON>. The most serious charge carries a maximum of seven years in prison and a $ 5,000 fine or double the amount illegally gained. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said he also would seek restitution. Arrested were attorney <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenichel </PERSON>, 65; his daughter, attorney <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenichel </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, 35; <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauer </PERSON>, 46; and her husband, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>, 53; all of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The elder <PERSON> Fenichel </PERSON> was released on $ 100,000 personal security bond. His daughter was released on $ 2,500 bail. The Lauers were released when they promised to pay $ 10,000 bail within two weeks.
