<SECOND>AM-Green Rocks, Adv 26,1149</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Monday June 26 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Intoxicating `Green Rocks' Part of Juarez's Plague of Waste</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> was alarmed when he found his sons sniffing green rocks that kids carried away from the municipal dump. Fourteen-year-old <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> and 18-year-old <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> lurched and stumbled in the unpaved streets, occasionally pulling a sock out of a pocket and sniffing it. The socks held a bright green, rocky substance that smelled like airplane glue or spray paint. When crushed and sniffed, it gave the same cheap highs. The rocks surfaced in March and quickly became the drug of choice around the vast dump, an area where the well-off live in cinderblock houses and others make do with cardboard huts. Young children flocked to it, according to dozens of worried parents interviewed by <PERSON> Juarez </PERSON> newspapers. `` It makes people stupid and aggressive _ more aggressive than a drunk,'' said the <PERSON> Campos </PERSON>, whose sons shoved and hit him when he confronted them. They `` would lie on the couch and would n't get up.'' The green rocks proved to be toxic waste dumped by a `` maquiladora,'' one of 275 U.S.-owned factories located in <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION> to take advantage of cheap labor. Mexican environmental suspect maquiladoras improperly dispose of half their hazardous waste. That would be hundreds of tons a year in <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION> alone. The officials in <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION> say they have gotten rid of the green rocks and cracked down on toxic wastes at the dump, but gangs of toughs known as `` cholos'' still collect and sell intoxicating substances. <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> did n't know any of that in late March when he took some of the rocks to a reform school principal. She did n't know what they were. About the same time, a woman walked into the <ORGANIZATION> Centro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Integracion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Juvenil </ORGANIZATION>, a drug treatment center for children, and told psychologist <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bueno </PERSON> that her 10-year-old son was sniffing green rocks. `` She said that at the dump, there were lots of other children who used this.'' <PERSON> Bueno </PERSON>, who estimates that about 200 children experimented with the substance, sent it to the Secretariat Urban Development and Ecology, or SEDUE _ the beleaguered equivalent of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. SEDUE identified it as solidified <PERSON> Kaltex </PERSON>, an industrial solvent containing toluene, a petroleum derivative that can cause lung damage. A doctor told <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> him the <PERSON> Kaltex </PERSON> did more than that to his sons. `` When they get married, they ca n't have children,'' <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> said. Infertility is one possible side effect when adolescents use inhalants like toluene, said Dr. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrasco </PERSON> of the La Fe family clinic in <LOCATION> south </LOCATION> <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, where inhalant abuse is widespread. If users do n't become infertile, their children are likely to be deformed. Inhalants harm the liver and kidneys and can cause organic brain syndrome _ characterized by loss of coordination, irritability, chronic confusion and nerve injury, <PERSON> Carrasco </PERSON> said. And they can destroy tear ducts. `` After a while, they ca n't even cry, and they're subject to eye infections,'' he said. `` I think inhalant abuse is one of the worst _ and it's one of the most available for young kids.'' Parents reported seeing cholos jumping onto trucks turning off Avenue of the <LOCATION> Aztecs </LOCATION> onto the dirt road leading to the dump. The cholos would toss five -, 10 - and 20-gallon plastic buckets of waste off to When SEDUE officials inspected the dump April 6, they found dozens of buckets of <LOCATION> Kaltex </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Campos </PERSON>, who kept several chunks of <LOCATION> Kaltex </LOCATION> as souvenirs, said a piece the size of his foot goes for 10,000 pesos _ about $ 4.35. In late April, SEDUE traced the Kaltex to <ORGANIZATION> Outboard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>, which makes parts for <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Evinrude </ORGANIZATION> outboard boat engines. Officials at the <LOCATION> Waukegan </LOCATION>, Wis.-based manufacturer referred all questions to <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Anklam </PERSON>, manufacturing engineer in the Juarez plant. <PERSON> Anklam </PERSON> said news reports about the solvent residue had been greatly exaggerated and that representatives from the factory and SEDUE scoured the dump in late April and found three five-gallon plastic buckets that had originated at <ORGANIZATION> Outboard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>, called Omex for short. `` Omex accepts the possibility that the three pails ... could have been dumped by accident at the Juarez landfill. It was just a human error, if in fact it is ours. A lot of companies use similar materials around here,'' said <PERSON> Anklam </PERSON>, adding that Omex is cooperating with SEDUE and acting legally. Mexican law requires hazardous waste from maquiladoras to be returned to their place of origin, usually the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law requires companies returning hazardous waste to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to notify the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which shares information with the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Meacham </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, said tracking waste through paperwork is time-consuming _ and even if the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> had no record of a company returning waste to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, it would n't mean much. `` If the wastes are from raw materials from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, they can be disposed of in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Or if it's recyclable, it can be recycled in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Or they can store their waste on-site in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> indefinitely.'' <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuela </PERSON> <PERSON> Salas </PERSON>, chief of <ORGANIZATION> SEDUE </ORGANIZATION>'s office in <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION>, said Omex is complying with Mexican law. She referred all other questions to <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>, communications chief for SEDUE. <PERSON> James </PERSON> did not return numerous calls to his home and office from The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Salas </PERSON> told the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Diario </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Juarez </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Omex </PERSON> was the first maquiladora to be caught throwing toxic waste into the Juarez dump. `` To ensure this does n't happen again, we're giving an identification number to each business that generates waste, to make it easier to watch them.'' But it is difficult for SEDUE to keep watch. The agency has 10 inspectors in <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION> to monitor 275 maquiladoras and at least 100 Mexican-owned factories. Faced with a crushing national debt, a severe housing shortage and a population boom that adds 1 million people to the work force a year, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s government has not been able to make environmental protection a high priority. So far, <ORGANIZATION> SEDUE </ORGANIZATION>'s plan does n't seem to be working. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>, the dump's foreman, said he does n't know what's in the scores of trucks that deposit waste in the landfill daily. Neither do the drivers, he said. But the cholos seem to know. They still wait at the corner where trucks turn to go to the dump. They still jump on, and they still toss buckets off the speeding trucks for collection later. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> takes part. `` There are 10 other kinds of intoxicants there,'' <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Campos </PERSON> said. `` Paint, adhesive ...'' He shrugged helplessly, lowered his gaze, and sighed.
