<HEAD>Fed Gives Morgan Subsidiary Permission to Underwrite Corporate Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has given final permission to a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to underwrite corporate debt, the first time the agency has granted that power to a commercial bank. In January, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> authorized <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> and four other large banks to expand their securities underwriting, but withheld final approval until it could review the management and financing of the banks' securities subsidiaries. That approval was given to <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> on Monday. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> is the first to get the final nod. The others with pending applications are <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Banks for some time have had the power to buy and sell <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government securities and to underwrite and deal in general obligation municipal bonds In January, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> ruled that banks could also underwrite corporate debt provided that the activity did not generate more than 5 percent of all securities income. Corporate debt underwriting within that limit will not violate the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investment banking, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> ruled. The agency is expected to decide early next year whether banks can engage in limited underwriting of corporate stock.
