<SECOND>PM-Time,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Look to Delaware Court For Key Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Speculation is growing that the courts may be the next key arena in the fight for control of media giant <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Time's stock price fell again Monday following the company's rejection last week of a $ 10.7 billion takeover bid by <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and its announcement of its own $ 14 billion, $ 70-a-share tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> In trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 5.62 -LCB- a share to close at $ 156.87 -LCB-. It declined $ 9 a share Friday. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> rose 37 -LCB- cents a share to hit $ 59.62 -LCB-, and was the most active <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> issue. Paramount shares gained $ 2.37 -LCB- a share to close at $ 60.50. Either deal would create one of the world's largest entertainment and media concerns, ensuring that an American company would be among the global communications giants in the 1990s. Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> announced in March that they planned to merge in a stock swap transaction and amended that deal Friday to provide that <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> would offer $ 70-a-share for half of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s 200 million shares followed by a merger in which Time would pay $ 70 in cash and securities for the rest. Paramount has vowed to press ahead with its efforts to acquire Time. Securities analysts said they expect Paramount to ask the <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, where all three companies are incorporated, for a decision on the legality of the Time offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. `` The game is n't over yet,'' said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> McAlpine </PERSON>, a media analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Clearly, the court is the next issue.'' Analysts expect Paramount will ask the court to determine whether <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> put itself up for sale by agreeing to merge with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> initially and whether <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> directors acted appropriately by agreeing to make the cash offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. Time has insisted it has not put itself up for sale, and that the cash offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> represented a revision of its original merger plan. Paramount has argued that Time has put itself up for sale, because <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> stockholders would have only had about a 40 percent interest in the merged company under the old plan. As a result, Paramount is expected to argue that Time should be subject to an auction _ including any Paramount bid. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Noble </PERSON>, who follows media stocks for <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said his analysis indicated that stock in the resulting <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> combination would be valued by the market at about $ 173 a share. But he said the fact that <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> still was trading well below the $ 70-a-share offered price `` implies there is still a lot of speculation about all three stocks and about what will really happen.''
