<FIRST>r f PM-UAWConvention Bjt   06-20 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAW Convention, Bjt,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Strikes Against Dissident Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs lead planned; Convention session starts at 3 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With two strikes against it, a dissident movement within the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union will try again, perhaps today, to make itself felt at the union's constitutional convention. The New Directions movement is proposing a resolution that would limit `` jointness'' in auto plants. The aim is to limit the growing practice of union and management joining together on a variety of projects inside and outside factories. It's a key issue for the strongest organized dissent in the 1 million member union in 40 years _ since the mid-1930s when <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuther </PERSON> took the reins of the union. If the voting on the `` jointness'' issue goes the way of other New Directions-backed resolutions, the movement may strike out at the convention. However, its leader, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, has said there is more grass-roots support for the movement than what shows up at the convention. The forces of the Administration Caucus, led by <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON>, have easily put out any fires of dissent on the convention floor. While hard voting figures are not available because tallies are taken by a show of hands, New Directions has n't received support from more than 20 percent of the 2,000 delegates attending the convention On Monday, New Directions forces were turned back in an attempt to require rank-and-file elections for the union's top national officers, including the president, secretary-treasurer and vice presidents. Currently those offices are filled through voting by the delegates at constitutional conventions. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> is expected to win a third three-year term in balloting Wednesday. Backers of the New Directions movement said a `` one-man, one-vote'' policy would make the union's leadership more accountable to the members. Administration Caucus members said nationwide campaigning would be too time consuming. Besides, they said, the system seems to be working now. But that did n't satisfy <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallett </PERSON> of Local 31 in <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION> `` They pay their union dues, they deserve the right to vote,'' he said from the floor during debate on the issue. But <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON> of Local 600 in <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, reading from the convention's constitution committee report, said: `` A referendum is only the outer shell of democracy. The convention system delivers the substance.'' The effort was defeated on a show-of-hands vote. On Sunday, the first day of the week-long convention, delegates turned aside another New Directions move challenging the seating of several local delegations from regions covering eight south-central states and parts of metropolitan <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. Also Monday, delegates heard a campaign-style speech by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, an unsuccessful candidate for the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, in his first major speech since being elected majority leader of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> two weeks ago, sounded themes similar to ones he and others raised during last year's campaign. As he did during the campaign, he focused on the nation's trade deficit, saying the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has `` made some good sounds on trade.'' `` It remains to be seen if they are tough,'' he added. `` If not, we're going to have the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> amendment or something like it.'' The congressman from <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> based a large part of his unsuccessful presidential campaign last year on trade issues. The legislation he proposed would have forced the president to take action against countries that traded unfairly with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` You can not compete against unfair competition,'' he said. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> also criticized the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, saying the nation needed to develop a comprehensive energy policy and to divert spending from military hardware to education and the fight against drugs. `` This is our time ... to make <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> great and good and strong again,'' he said.
