<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell against most major foreign currencies in early European trading today. Gold prices were little changed. Currency dealers said the dollar's short-term trend is downward as a result of confusion created by last week's selloff. But they said the outlook for the longer term remains bullish as there's still underlying demand for dollars One trader in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> said the dollar-yen exchange rate has remained surprisingly stable because of continued strong demand for dollars out of the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, adding to the market's general confusion. He predicted that the dollar's downward correction could last one week, before bullish sentiments would take the upper hand again. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 1.70 yen to a closing 143.80 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 143.63 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday's rates, included: 1.9708 West German marks, down from 1.9735; 1.7047 Swiss francs, up from 1.7045; 6.6810 French francs, down from 6.6940; 2.2205 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2351; 1,427.00 Italian lire, down from 1,439.75; and 1.1985 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1991 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost $ 1.5575 to buy one pound, compared with $ 1.5485 late Monday. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price for gold of $ 366.50 an ounce at midmorning, unchanged from late Monday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 366.50 compared with $ 366.25 late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose 93 cents to close at a bid $ 367.70. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 5.35 a troy ounce, down from Monday's $ 5.37.
