<HEAD>Dollar Tumbles, Japanese Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell sharply against the Japaense yen today, while the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s key index rebounded. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 220.29 points, or 0.67 percent, finishing at 33,233.47. The dollar closed at 143.80 yen, down 1.70 yen from Monday's 145.50-yen finish It opened at 143.75 yen and moved between 143.25 yen and 144.00 yen. Traders said most investors were adjusting their dollar holdings, mainly because of uncertainties over the direction of the dollar-yen rate after large swings last week. The dollar closed Thursday at 151.30 yen, its highest in almost two years, and then fell 6.25 yen the next day. <PERSON> Yoshitsugu </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanada </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> trader, said investors were buying dollars at the 143-yen level, while Japanese trading houses were selling as the dollar approached 144 yen. `` In mixed trading, the dollar has been gradually falling,'' <PERSON> Hamada </PERSON> said, adding that most investors no longer are looking for an abrupt rise against the yen. But this does not mean bullishness about the dollar has been totally reversed, he said. `` Now is the adjustment phase after the dollar's rapid rise to the 151-yen level last week,'' said <PERSON> Hamada </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> reportedly was selling dollars to support the yen, but the amount was not known. The central bank does not comment on its foreign exchange activities. On the stock exchange, dealers said the yen's surge against the dollar reassured Japanese investors, encouraging stock purchases. <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> analyst <PERSON> Masahiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Umemori </PERSON> said, `` The market rebounded by itself mainly because of recent stability in foreign exchange.'' `` It's too early to say the strong yen is back, but the foreign exchange's stability was at least good news for stock trading,'' he said, noting that the index had fallen more than 1,100 points last week because of the dollar's sharp rise against the yen. Trading, however, was still inactive due to lingering uncertainties over currency movements, <PERSON> Umemori </PERSON> said. Volume on the first section was estimated at 700 million shares, up from 450 million the previous day. Among gainers were electricals including <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, as well as steel and shipbuilding issuees.
