<FIRST>u f PM-LotusSoftware 1stLd-Writethru   06-20 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lotus Software, 1st Ld-Writethru,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lotus Ready To Ship Long Delayed Spreadsheet Software</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede CAMBRIDGE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with announcement at annual meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 18 months of delays, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said today it has begun shipping its Release 3, an improved version of the best-selling 1-2-3 computer software. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Manzi </PERSON>, the company's 37-year-old chairman, made the announcement at <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION>' annual meeting in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. With the embarrassing delays last year, `` Lotus and Release 3 had become the moral equivalent of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> in the World Series,'' <PERSON> Manzi </PERSON> said. `` We have come through a very tough period, and I believe we have proved our mettle,'' he said. A key feature of the new software is the ability to display data in three dimensions. Other computer spreadsheets show information along two axes, allowing, for example, a store manager who wants to analyze his seasonal sales pattern to put products along one axis and time periods along the other. If he has several stores, however, the manager faces an additional headache. With Release 3, he can cure it by creating a third axis, representing various stores or geographic regions. After three years and tens of millions of dollars in development costs, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> is betting that 3-D software, unlike movies, will turn out to be more than a quick fad. Not everyone is sure. `` I think three dimensionality is a desirable function for a certain percentage of the market, but what percentage, I do n't know,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherlund </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> `` Not everyone needs it.'' Lotus, founded in 1982, has grown from a handful of employees to more than 2,600 worldwide on the strength of 1-2-3, its original product and still the source of nearly two-thirds of its sales, which are projected at more than $ 500 million this year. But to keep ahead of competitors like <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Redmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Borland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Scotts </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> has had to continually upgrade the program's features. For the top-secret Release 3 project, which <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> code named `` Godiva,'' the firm three years ago assembled a small team of engineers that quickly grew to more than 100 people. A confident <PERSON> Manzi </PERSON> announced in April 1987 that Release 3 would be out in early 1988. But design and management problems, about which the company has said little, intervened. <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> said in February 1988 that Release 3 would not be ready until late in the second quarter of 1988. A month later, the target date was pushed back to the fourth quarter. Then, last October, the company announced a further delay, until the second quarter of 1989. With its repeated failure to meet its own deadlines, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION>' earnings and stock price plunged, and its competitors picked up market share <PERSON> Manzi </PERSON>, a former management consultant who had taken over from <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Kapor </PERSON> in 1986, was stung by intensely personal negative publicity. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Digate </PERSON>, the executive in charge of spreadsheets, resigned. Industry wags said the company was pioneering a new class of products called `` vaporware'' _ software that disappears every time it is about to be introduced. But Lotus apparently turned the corner last year when it brought in <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> manager, to head up the project. He injected discipline into the project team and got Release 3 into field test in February. As a result, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> stock has largely recovered, trading recently at around $ 26 a share, close to its 52-week high of $ 26.75 and far above its low for the year of $ 14.75. Competitors are still close on the firm's heels, with <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> steadily enhancing its Excel software, the No. 2 spreadsheet on the market, and <ORGANIZATION> Borland </ORGANIZATION> reportedly working on a 3-D version of its Quattro program. At <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION>' annual meeting today in the Berklee Performance Center attended by more than 400 people, the company showed a wide-screen television transmission from its manufacturing center in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> with boxes of Release 3 rolling off an assembly line and being packed for shipment to customers across the country. The delays have `` cost them a lot of clout in the market and tarnished their reputation,'' <PERSON> Sherlund </PERSON> said in advance of the announcement. `` Now it's their time to shine.''
</TEXT>
