<HEAD>Silver Drops As Dollar Gains, Inflation Fears Wane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Silver futures prices slid about 9 cents an ounce Tuesday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the dollar strengthened and other commodity prices fell, easing inflation fears. Gold futures prices also dropped. On other markets, grain and soybean futures fell, energy futures were mixed, and livestock and meat prices were mixed. Silver settled 9 cents to 9.1 cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 5.25 a troy ounce; gold was 70 cents to $ 1 lower with August at $ 369.60 a troy ounce. Precious metals prices had been on the upswing, rising in five of the six previous sessions on perceptions that inflation was gathering steam. Precious metals are considered a safe investment in times of rising prices. Inflation worries had intensified after sharp increases in most commodity futures prices on Monday, and many precious-metals traders expected the rally to continue Tuesday. Instead, most commodity prices opened steady or lower. The dollar began the day on a weak note, which supported the precious metals early in the session, but it turned sharply higher by the end of the day and became a major negative influence on the metals. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Steel </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said precious-metals traders will continue to watch the dollar for direction. `` If we see continued dollar strength over the summer, I think the metals will have no other option but to go lower,'' he said. Metals broker <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said further selling was prompted by the July silver contract's inability to push above $ 5.39 an ounce, the previous day's high July silver topped out at $ 5.38 on its third rally attempt, and many traders then gave up and sold the market, <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON> said. Corn and soybean futures prices dropped on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> as wetter weather forecasts for the Corn Belt took the edge off drought fears. Wheat futures also retreated. The corn and soybean markets lost about half of the ground they gained Monday, when the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> looked to be due for an extended spell of hot, dry weather. But Tuesday's forecasts predicted rain in the northern and western Corn Belt by the end of this week, and selling pressure was strong from the opening bell. Wheat settled unchanged to 2 \ cents lower with July at $ 3.95 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 2 -RCB- cents to 5 -LCB- cents lower with July at $ 2.66 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 4 cents lower with July at $ 1.68 \ a bushel; soybeans were 8 -LCB- cents to 12 \ cents lower with July at $ 7.36 The July crude-oil contract expired with a $ 1.33 loss at $ 19.53 a barrel after a volatile trading session that saw the price whipsaw from $ 19.02 to $ 21.30 a barrel. Experts said the wild action on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> signified no new supply-and-demand developments and was solely a function of the contract's expiration. Other West Texas Intermediate crude-oil contracts settled 8 cents lower to 4 cents higher with August at $ 18.88 a barrel; heating oil was .35 cent to .45 cent lower with July at 45.69 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .17 cent to .48 cent higher with July at 59.17 cents a gallon. Livestock and meat futures finished mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in a session featuring profit-taking after Monday's sharp runup. Live cattle settled .28 cent lower to .75 cent higher with June at 73.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .18 cent to .47 cent lower with August at 81.35 cents a pound; live hogs were .55 cent lower to .18 cent higher with June at 49.15 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .20 cent lower to .67 cent higher with July at 34.50 cents a pound.
