<HEAD>Crude Oil Plunges; Refined Products Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil prices plunged more than $ 1 a barrel in thin trading Tuesday while other petroleum products ended mixed. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the July contract for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, finished $ 1.33 lower at $ 19.53 a barrel, after gaining 91 cents on Monday. Other contract months were mixed. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, an energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, attributed the sell-off in crude to the fact that the near-month contract was set to expire on Tuesday. He noted that prices started out sharply higher, with the July contract up as much as $ 21.30 a barrel, but that they plunged later in the session as demand fizzled. `` There really were no fundamental reasons'' for the decline, <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON> said. The drop in crude helped pull down heating oil. The July contract for wholesale No. 2 heating oil slipped 0.37 cent to 45.69 cents a gallon, after settling 0.86 cent higher on Monday. Among other refined petroleum products, unleaded gasoline for July delivery rose 0.17 cent to 59.17 cents a gallon. The contract was up 0.86 cent the previous session.
