<HEAD>Lotus Ships Long-Awaited Release 3 Spreadsheet Software</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After an 18-month delay that drove down its stock and depressed its earnings, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it has begun shipping an improved version of its best-selling 1-2-3 computer software. More than 400 stockholders burst into cheers at <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION>' annual meeting as a live video hookup showed boxes of the long-awaited spreadsheet program, named Release 3, rolling off an assembly line at the company's <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> manufacturing center. With that triumph behind him, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Manzi </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION>' 37-year-old chairman, was able to talk about the embarrassing delays with humor. `` Lotus and Release 3 had become the moral equivalent of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> in the World Series,'' he said. `` ... We have come through a very tough period, and I believe we have proved our mettle.'' <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Lotzgesell </PERSON>, an analyst with the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> brokerage house of <PERSON> Ragen </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackenzie </PERSON>, said the delay in producing Release 3 was a boon to competitors like <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Redmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Borland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Scotts </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Lotus, founded in 1982, once had a near lock on the $ 600 million-a-year market for computer spreadsheets Now, <ORGANIZATION> Microsoft </ORGANIZATION>'s Excel program has about 12 percent of the market, <ORGANIZATION> Borland </ORGANIZATION>'s Quattro has between 5 and 10 percent, and various other programs have about 10 percent, <PERSON> Lotzgesell </PERSON> said `` Wih people waiting and waiting and waiting -LRB- for Release 3 -RRB-, <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> did lose customers,'' she said. `` Now they may win some back.'' Release 3 originally was due out in early 1988. When <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> delayed its arrival three times, reportedly because of problems transferring the basic machine code into the computer language `` C,'' many analysts cut their 1989 earnings projections by 20 percent or more. <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> stock also plunged, although it has since bounced back to about $ 26 a share from a 52-week low of $ 14.75. Now, said analyst <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherlund </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the question is whether Release 3 can recapture the momentum for <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION>, which has 2,600 employees and reported sales of $ 468.5 million last year. One of the key advantages of Release 3 is the ability to display data in three dimensions, showing a row of up to 256 spreadsheets. But that ability makes the program something of a memory hog; to run it efficiently, a computer must have the latest generation of <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> 286 or 386 microchips and more than 1 megabyte of random access memory. Release 2.2, a version for less powerful, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> XT - and PC-compatible machines, is due out later this year Other versions, including one rich in graphics and one for Apple Macintosh computers, also are planned. <PERSON> Manzi </PERSON>, who took over from <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kapor </PERSON> in 1986, endured harsh criticism for the company's delays and for his compensation, which totaled more than $ 26 million in 1987. But on Tuesday, he was clearly enjoying himself. Thanking the team of more than 100 engineers and programmers who produced Release 3, he told stockholders that `` These people have shown unbelievable dedication, unbelievable skill, and an equally unbelievable ability to eat cold pizza late at night.''
