<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Survey Says Shrinking Youth Population Changing Consumer Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A decline in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s young adult population will be accompanied by a rise in average household income so the age group's buying power will hold steady, a research group said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the pool of young people will shrink significantly as the 20th century comes to a close due to a slowdown in the birth rate that began in the 1960s. The number of people between the ages of 20 and 35 will fall by about 10 million during the next 15 years from about 63 million in 1985, forecasts say. <PERSON> Fabian </PERSON> <PERSON> Linden </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s consumer research center, said over the past decade and a half young people have been the biggest growth segment of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumer market `` But in the years ahead they will hold considerably less promise for marketers of a wide variety of products and services,'' <PERSON> Linden </PERSON> said. He estimated that currently one out of every four dollars of total household income flows to homes headed by persons under 35 years old. The amount is expected to fall to less than one dollar out of every five by the year 2000. However, the real buying power of this age group is n't expected to contract. `` The increase in average household earnings over the next decade will offset the decline in the number of households,'' <PERSON> Linden </PERSON> said. `` Additionally, because there will be fewer available American workers between the ages of 20 and 35, they will likely receive higher pay.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> is a nonprofit research-oriented group supported by businesses, trade and professional organizations, government agencies, unions and others.
</TEXT>
