<HEAD>Government: Racketeering Defendants Made Illegal Trades Like a Yo-Yo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 21 grafs to RECAST lead, UPDATE throughout with defense
lawyers opening statements, more prosecution arguments, CORRECT yo-yo quote;
PICKS UP 13th graf pvs, `Much of...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government prosecutor charged Tuesday that officials of <ORGANIZATION> Princeton-Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LP </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> illegally bought and sold stocks in a widespread tax fraud scheme amounting to `` plain, old-fashioned cheating.'' In opening arguments in the first racketeering case ever involving securities trading, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said the six defendants engaged in a `` very simple criminal scheme'' between 1984 and 1986 to generate phony tax losses. He also said prosecutors would play incriminating tapes in court, one of which includes a <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> trader telling a Princeton-Newport partner, `` Welcome to the world of being a sleaze.'' `` This is a case about cheating,'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said in a packed courtroom at <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` These defendants are wealthy, successful men, men who decided they were above the law, who decided they could break the law without being caught.'' On trial are five officials of the defunct investment partnership and former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> trader <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON>. The case overlaps the government's indictment of former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> financier <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>. Neither of the firms is on trial. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> alleged that <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> via <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> purchased stocks from Princeton-Newport, then sold them back a short time later to create bogus losses that <PERSON> Princeton-Newport </PERSON> declared as tax deductions. The indictment in the case, handed up last August, alleged $ 13 million in bogus tax losses. Moving his left hand up and down, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> equated the alleged illegal trades with the motion of a yo-yo. `` These sales were on a string,'' he said. `` When the Princeton-Newport defendants sent those securities out, they sent them out waiting for the moment when they could bring them back with a little tug of the hand.'' `` When Princeton-Newport defendants went to the government and took that tax deduction, that was a fraud,'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> added. But <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON>, attorney for Princeton-Newport managing partner <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, said the tax trades were `` appropriate, proper and lawful'' and made in response to changes in federal tax laws in June 1984. `` Each loss involved in this case is a real loss,'' he said. In another alleged scheme, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> claimed <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON>, with the help of the Princeton-Newport defendants, illegally drove down the stock price of <ORGANIZATION> C.O.M.B. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 before a <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> offering of $ 25 million in bonds to the Minneapolis-based merchandiser. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> did not explain the motivation for the alleged scheme. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> also told the jury of nine women and three men that the alleged bogus stock `` parking'' trades also involved <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Akroyd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Smithers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. Those two firms cooperated with the government. They were not charged. In an illegal `` parking'' deal, one party agrees to purchase a block of stock under an agreement to sell it back at a prearranged time and price, usually to skirt federal tax or stock ownership disclosure laws. In addition to <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, on trial are <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabinowitz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarzecki </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkman </PERSON>, all partners in the investment firm; and <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smotorick </PERSON>, <PERSON> Princeton-Newport </PERSON>'s comptroller <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said prosecutors would play tapes of conversations between <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Princeton-Newport </LOCATION> employees discussing the alleged illegal deals. The tapes, made as part of normal Princeton-Newport business activities, were seized during a raid on the firm's headquarters in December 1987 <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said one tape contains <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> telling <PERSON> Zarzecki </PERSON> after the latter made a C.O.M.B transaction in April 1985: `` You're a sleaze-bag.'' `` You taught me, man,'' <PERSON> Zarzecki </PERSON> is said to reply on the tape. `` Welcome to the world of being a sleaze,'' <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> said, according to <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>. Much of the evidence in the <LOCATION> Princeton-Newport </LOCATION> case also is expected to be used against <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, the former head of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s junk bond department, who was charged in March in a separate 98-count racketeering indictment. <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> also is charged in that case. The charges against <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> include dealings he allegedly had with Princeton-Newport, which was based in <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and went out of business shortly after its officials were indicted last August. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> conceded that none of the defendants made any money in the alleged illegal deals, but attributed that to accountants' errors. He said that fact did not exonerate the men. The Princeton-Newport trial is the first in which the racketeering statute, which carries heavy sentences, fines and forfeiture of alleged illicit profits upon conviction, has been used against officials of a securities firm.
