<HEAD>Tyson Increases Bid For Holly Farms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Tyson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest poultry processor, pressed its attempt Tuesday to take over <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> by raising a tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> stock to $ 70 a share, a bid worth more than $ 1.2 billion. Tyson of <LOCATION> Springdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, has been trying to take over <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> since last October, and the Memphis-based <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> has been struggling since November to merge with <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb </LOCATION>. `` We are delighted that <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON> has now decided to raise its bid,'' <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Nachbar </PERSON> said in a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that has refereed the <LOCATION> Tyson-Holly-ConAgra </LOCATION> squabble. `` We do expect the <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> board to meet within the next five business days to consider the proposal,'' <PERSON> Nachbar </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> urged its 5,500 shareholders to hold on to their 18.1 million shares until the company's board meets to review the latest Tyson bid. In raising its tender offer from $ 63.50, <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON> also said its new bid was no longer conditioned on removal of an asset sales agreement established late last year between <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION>. That agreement is at the heart of a legal fight launched by <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON>. The latest merger proposal for <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> was announced May 20 and is based on a stock swap, while <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON>'s bid is for cash. <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> expect to call shareholder votes next month on their proposed merger. When the proposal was announced, <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> said it was worth $ 74 a share based on market prices at the time. The <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court has been told, however, that the offer likely would be worth around $ 68 a share by the time the agreement could be settled. In addition to raising its offer, <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON> also filed a court petition Tuesday seeking to force <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> to dissolve a shareholder rights plan containing a `` poison pill'' aimed at making a takeover more costly for an aggressor. Vice Chancellor <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartnett </PERSON> rejected a similar <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON> attack on that plan June 14 while clearing the way for shareholder votes on the proposed merger. The shareholder rights plan, adopted in October, would give <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> stockholders a price break on additional shares in the event of a takeover. The battle for <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> began last year when <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON> offered a deal valued at $ 49.50 a share through a cash and stock swap. <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> managers rejected that offer as insufficient and have pointed out several times during the ensuing takeover attempt that their resistance has raised the amount of money their stockholders will make if the company is sold. <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION>'s original merger offer called for swapping 1.875 shares of <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> stock for each <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> share traded. The current proposal calls for a swap of 2.1 shares. Tyson Foods processes 16.5 million chickens a week and has announced expansion plans to push that to 17.5 million by the end of next month. <ORGANIZATION> Holly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farms </ORGANIZATION> is a diversified company heavily involved in fresh chicken sales. <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> is a diversified company specializing in food and agricultural services.
