<HEAD>Paramount, Warner Trade Charges in Time Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Longer version on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, pursuing <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> with a a $ 10.7 billion takeover bid, has asked federal regulators to set aside rulings allowing Time to transfer control of its cable TV systems to the company <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> wants to create by buying <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, argued that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s plans for creating a voting trust to take temporary custody of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> stock violates cable laws that give local authorities the right to approve transfers of cable licenses The filings at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> were the latest round in the manueverings over whether <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> can acquire Time or whether <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> buys <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> in deals that would create the world's largest entertainment and media conglomerate. Lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> said in documents filed with the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> that <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> had misrepresented to Time stockholders the nature of the transfer of control. Paramount also said Time had written to state attorneys general asking them to oppose <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal without notifying Paramount of the letters. These actions `` raise substantial and material questions about Time's character qualifications,'' <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> said in asking the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to set aside its previous approval of the license transfers pending an <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> investigation. Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> announced in March they had agreed to merge in a stock swap, and proceeded to secure appropriate regulatory clearances. Paramount launched its hostile bid for Time on June 6, just 17 days before <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shareholders were to have voted on the merger. Time rejected <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s offer and revised its merger agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> to call for a $ 14 billion tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. The battle is expected to be waged in court in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, where all three companies are incorporated. Paramount earlier this month asked the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> for permission to deposit any <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shares it may acquire in a voting trust that would be headed by former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rumsfeld </PERSON> pending <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> approval of the transfer of 99 cable television franchises and licenses held by <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s 82-percent-owned subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Harding </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said Tuesday that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s request `` would violate the recent cable act because <PERSON> Rumsfeld </PERSON> has n't gotten consent from any of these cities for the transfers. <PERSON> Harding </PERSON>, echoing assertions Time made in a June 13 filing with the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s plan would `` undermine the delicate balance'' established in the 1984 Cable Act for regulation of cable systems by local authorities. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> asked the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> late Monday to deny the application made by <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> for expedited consent for the trust arrangement for temporary custody of any Time shares that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> acquires. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s plan called for an `` unprecedented extension'' to the cable TV industry of <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> rules that cover hostile tender offers for broadcast licenses. `` Such an extension of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> tender offer policy would emasculate the significant role in cable franchising mandated for local authorities by the Cable Communications Policy Act of 1984,'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> also said, among other things, that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s plan was faulty because <PERSON> Rumsfeld </PERSON> was being paid $ 250,000 and thus was not an independent trustee; that a voting trust was invalid because <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s cable systems were affiliated with <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s Madison Square Garden and <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> networks; and that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> might end up owning TV and cable systems in the same region in violation of federal cross-ownership regulations `` Paramount's so-called tender offer is so riddled with conditions, loopholes and escape hatches as to be essentially illusory,'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said.
