<HEAD>Seidman Discussing Plan To Take On Greater Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON>, who would become the new deposit insurance czar under legislation moving through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, is talking to the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> about an idea that would enhance his power over the savings and loan bailout <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON> is angling for greater authority over the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a new entity that will be created to close or merge insolvent savings and loan institutions and dispose of real estate repossessed by the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls, said a well-informed industry official, speaking on condition of anonymity. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> chairman is said to be proposing that his own organization's board, rather than a single person, be appointed chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON>, in a telephone interview Tuesday, declined to say his agency is advocating the idea, but he described it as `` worth exploring'' and `` feasible. `` It's not our idea. It came from a suggestion that the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- the congressional <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- made. We have been talking to <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> about it,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, under legislation that passed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last week and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in April, will have the mammoth task of spending $ 50 billion in new bailout funds and of handling $ 300 billion to $ 500 billion of bad loans and property. The legislation does not spell out how the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> will be structured beyond the composition of its board, which will be headed by the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary, and the fact that it must hire a chief executive officer. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> is getting the job of insuring savings and loan deposits, in addition to the commercial bank deposits it already guarantees. However, the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>'s relationship to the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is left unclear. Treasury officials have said they envision the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> as an oversight agency, with fewer than 100 employees, which would hire others to do its work. Presumably, the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>, because it has already taken over the 221 <ORGANIZATION> worst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls and has the largest pool of experienced real estate liquidators in the government, would be the biggest contractor, with private firms also getting pieces of the work. However, <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON> has said he does not want his agency to get expanded responsibility without added authority to control the conditions and terms under which it does the additional work. <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON> said if the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> were not given the added authority, and were simply a contractor of the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, it would want to pick and choose what S & amp; L liquidation work it wanted. `` We can contract to do what we think is good for -LRB- our -RRB- agency to do and we would n't have responsibility for the overall operation. We would contract to do such jobs as were attractive to both sides,'' he said. However, that would probably require the administration to make the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> a larger and more complex bureaucracy than it now wants. Assistant Treasury Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> said the administration has planned all along for the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> to take the lead role in disposing of failed S & amp; Ls. At issue, he said, is the vigor of administration oversight. The administration sees the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s chief executive officer as a `` full-time oversight officer,'' he said. `` No one likes the idea of a full-time person overseeing them. But our view is we're required to have oversight,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> `` wants as much independence as -LRB- it -RRB- can get, but there's a limit as to what can be done on that.'' He said the administration is working to more precisely define the RTC-FDIC relationship in time for a definition to be included in <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L legislation, which is expected to be on President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s desk by early August, following a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference and final congressional approval in July. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who owns an <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, real estate liquidation firm which has worked for the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>, said there are two factions within the agency. One is composed of <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> veterans `` who do n't appear interested in taking on this enormous problem.'' The other faction, he said, consists of `` the future <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> Trumps of the world'' who want to expand the agency. `` I think <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON> is with the young Turks,'' the industry official said.
