<HEAD>Religious Group Plans to Announce Advertiser Boycott Plans July 17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A religious group that plans to target one or more advertisers for a boycott based on the television shows the companies sponsor said Tuesday they plan to announce their selection July 17. The group, <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leaders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Responsible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> or Clear-TV, said it is analyzing data collected during from the recent TV sweeps period to compose its list. <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evangelicals </ORGANIZATION> and chairman of the group, said the data was collected by about 3,000 people watching TV in 33 states. He said network advertisers were asked three times before the sweeps period, April 27 through May 24, to be responsible in the placement of their commercials by avoiding programs with gratuitous sex, violence, profanity and anti-Christian stereotyping. Some industry watchers say efforts in the early 1980s to boycott advertisers failed. But advertisers have in recent months canceled ad plans following complaints from some individuals or groups unhappy with the content of programs such as <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Saturday Night Live'' and the <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> television network's `` Married ... with Children.'' Clear-TV, based in <LOCATION> Wheaton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, says it is a coalition of 1,600 <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> leaders with constituencies totaling 60 million people.
