<HEAD>UAW Convention Defeats Third Motion By Dissident Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to RESTORE overline, LaserPhoto line.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ANS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> convention turned aside Tuesday an attempt to limit joint labor-management programs at auto plants, dealing a dissident group its third major defeat in as many days. In a show-of-hands vote, delegates to the union's triennial constitutional convention rejected a move that would have forced the international union to support locals that oppose the team management style. The so-called jointness resolution is a cornerstone of the disagreement between the New Directions movement and the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s leadership The dissidents claim the joint programs endanger jobs and rob the union of its strength. The Administration Caucus, which represents the union's administration, contends that change in the workplace is necessary, and that New Directions supporters do n't recognize that. `` It makes me wonder where they -LRB- dissidents -RRB- have been in the last 15 years,'' delegate <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> of Local 1895 in <LOCATION> Broken </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arrow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, area said during debate on the matter. But New Directions member <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON>, president of Local 909 in <LOCATION> Warren </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, said the joint programs represent a union-breaking strategy. `` I submit to you that jointness is their attempt to co-opt our union,'' he said. The joint labor-management programs grew out of the auto industry's slump in the early 1980s and the threat of foreign competition. The New Directions effort also suggested that the union abandon its seat on the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> board of directors, now held by union President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> bristled at the suggestion. `` It's a lonely place on that board ... but it's the only voice of the workers,'' he said. After the loss, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, the leader of the New Directions movement, said he thought the debate was worthwhile and that he hoped delegates would return to their locals and talk about the convention with the rank and file. `` The rank and file ultimately will find ways to express themselves,'' he said. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> declined to say exactly how or when that expression may come. He did say he expected there would be a New Directions presence at <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> prebargaining meetings next year. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s contracts with the Big Three automakers expire on Sept. 14, 1990 Before the debate, the third day of the convention got off to a loud start as a parade of dissidents marched into the hall, waving signs and shouting. It was the first organized demonstration during the convention by New Directions forces, the strongest voice opposing <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> leadership in 40 years. New Directions, which has about 20 percent of the delegates in its corner, lost votes on two other major issues it brought to the convention. One involved a credentials fight over certain delegates from <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> regions in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> and metropolitan <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. The other would have required that the union abandon its practice of electing top national officers at conventions and substitute for it a national referendum of the rank and file.
